nodes.def: A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the distal phalanges of the hand. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.

nodes.label: Partial duplication of the middle phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the middle phalanges of the hand. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the hallux
Absent epiphyses of the toes
nodes.def: Absence of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the toes.

nodes.label: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the toes
Epiphyseal stippling of toe phalanges
nodes.def: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of phalanges of the toes.

nodes.label: Broad distal phalanx of the toes
nodes.def: Increased width of the distal phalanx of toe of one or more toes.

nodes.label: Curved distal toe phalanx
nodes.def: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more distal toe phalanges.

nodes.label: Patchy sclerosis of distal toe phalanx
nodes.def: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the distal phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanges of the toes
Patchy sclerosis of middle phalanx of toe
nodes.def: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the middle phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

nodes.label: Broad proximal phalanx of toe
nodes.def: An increase in width of one ore more proximal toe phalanges.

nodes.label: Bullet-shaped proximal toe phalanx
nodes.def: An abnormal morphology of one or more of the proximal phalanges of the toes, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

nodes.label: Curved proximal toe phalanx
nodes.def: A deviation from the normal straight shape of a proximal phalanx of one or more toes.

nodes.label: Patchy sclerosis of proximal toe phalanx
nodes.def: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the proximal phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

nodes.label: Absent epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Bracket epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: An abnormality of the distal phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

nodes.label: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Enlarged epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Irregular epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Pseudoepiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: A secondary ossification center in the distal phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

nodes.label: Small epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Stippling of the epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Triangular epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Absent epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Bracket epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: An abnormality of the middle phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

nodes.label: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Enlarged epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Irregular epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Pseudoepiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: A secondary ossification center in the middle phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

nodes.label: Small epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Stippling of the epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Triangular epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Absent epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Bracket epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: An abnormality of the proximal phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

nodes.label: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Irregular epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Pseudoepiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: A secondary ossification center in the proximal phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

nodes.label: Small epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Stippling of the epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Abnormal salivary gland morphology
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the salivary glands, the exocrine glands that produce saliva.

nodes.label: Abnormal coccyx morphology
nodes.def: Any structural abnormality of the coccyx.

nodes.label: Abnormal middle ear morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the morphology or structure of the middle ear.

nodes.label: EEG with generalized slow activity
nodes.def: Diffuse slowing of cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating long-chain fatty-acid concentration
nodes.def: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a long-chain fatty acid in the blood circulation.

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating fatty-acid anion concentration
nodes.def: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a fatty acid anion in the blood circulation.

nodes.label: Abnormality of lipoprotein cholesterol concentration
nodes.def: An abnormal increase or decrease in the level of lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the intrinsic pathway
nodes.def: An abnormality of the intrinsic pathway (also known as the contact activation pathway) of the coagulation cascade.

nodes.label: Abnormal renal cortex morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the cortex of the kidney.

nodes.label: EEG with focal spikes
nodes.def: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec.

nodes.label: EEG with focal spike waves
nodes.def: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

nodes.label: Abnormal morphology of the vestibule of the inner ear
nodes.def: A morphological abnormality of the vestibule, the central part of the osseous labyrinth that is situated medial to the tympanic cavity, behind the cochlea, and in front of the semicircular canals.

nodes.label: Abnormal inner ear morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of the internal part of the ear.

nodes.label: Age of death
nodes.def: The age group when the cessation of life happens.

nodes.label: Abnormal lacrimal punctum morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the lacrimal punctum, an opening on the eyelid close to the medial canthus that drains tears from the conjunctival sac into the lacrimal duct in the same eyelid.

nodes.label: Abnormal branching pattern of the aortic arch
nodes.def: A deviance from the norm of the origin or course of the right brachiocephalic artery, the left common carotid artery, the left subclavian artery or the proximal vertebral arteries.

nodes.label: Abnormal axial skeleton morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the axial skeleton, which comprises the skull, the vertebral column, the ribs and the sternum.

nodes.label: Mixed hypo- and hyperpigmentation of the skin
Increased adipose tissue
nodes.def: An increase in adipose tissue mass by hyperplastic growth (increase in the number of adipocytes) or by hypertrophic growth (increase in the size of adipocytes occurring primarily by lipid accumulation within the cell).

nodes.label: Fragmentation of the metacarpal epiphyses
nodes.def: Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the metacarpals.

nodes.label: Metacarpal pseudoepiphysis
nodes.def: A pseudoepiphysis is a secondary ossification center distinct from the normal epiphysis. The normal metacarpal epiphyses are located at the distal ends of the metacarpal bones. Accessory epiphyses (which are also known as pseudoepiphyses) can also occasionally be observed at the proximal ends of the metacarpals, usually involving the 2nd metacarpal bone.

nodes.label: Abnormal urine hormone level
nodes.def: An abnormal concentration of a hormone in the urine.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 2nd toe
Duplication of the phalanges of the 2nd toe
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of a phalanx of second toe.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 3rd toe
Abnormality of the distal phalanx of the 3rd toe
Abnormality of the middle phalanx of the 3rd toe
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 4th toe
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 5th toe
Polydactyly
nodes.def: A congenital anomaly characterized by the presence of supernumerary fingers or toes.

nodes.label: Irregular epiphyses
nodes.def: An alteration of the normally smooth contour of the epiphysis leading to an irregular appearance.

nodes.label: Small epiphyses
nodes.def: Reduction in the size or volume of epiphyses.

nodes.label: Premature epimetaphyseal fusion
nodes.def: Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at each end of a long bone, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.

nodes.label: Cutaneous syndactyly of toes
nodes.def: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between adjacent foot digits that involves at least half of the proximodistal length of one of the two involved digits; or, a soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between two digits of the foot that does not meet the prior objective criteria.

nodes.label: Aplasia of the distal phalanges of the toes
nodes.def: Absence of the distal phalanges of the toes.

nodes.label: Abnormal zygomatic bone morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the zygomatic bone.

nodes.label: Short metatarsal
nodes.def: Diminished length of a metatarsal bone, with resultant proximal displacement of the associated toe.

nodes.label: Abnormal myelination
nodes.def: Any anomaly in the process by which myelin sheaths are formed and maintained around neurons.

nodes.label: Abnormal sperm morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of sperm.

nodes.label: Abnormal lymph-node germinal center morphology
nodes.def: Any phenotypic abnormality of germinal centers of a lymph node.

nodes.label: Incomitant strabismus
nodes.def: Strabismus in which the angle of deviation differs depending upon the direction of gaze or according to which eye is fixing, associated with: (i) defective movement of the eye, (ii) asymmetrical accommodative effort.

nodes.label: Abnormal small intestinal mucosa morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of the mucous lining of the small intestine.

nodes.label: Bullet-shaped distal phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: Short and wide distal phalanges that taper distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

nodes.label: Curved distal phalanges of the hand
Osteolytic defects of the distal phalanges of the hand
Patchy sclerosis of distal phalanx of finger
nodes.def: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the distal phalanges of the hand.

nodes.label: Broad middle phalanx of finger
nodes.def: Increased width of the middle phalanx of finger.

nodes.label: Bullet-shaped middle phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: Any of the middle phalanges with short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

nodes.label: Curved middle phalanges of the hand
Osteolytic defects of the middle phalanges of the hand
Patchy sclerosis of middle phalanx of finger
nodes.def: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the middle phalanges of the hand.

nodes.label: Symphalangism of middle phalanx of finger
nodes.def: Fusion of a middle phalanx of a finger with another bone.

nodes.label: Triangular shaped middle phalanges of the hand
Curved proximal phalanges of the hand
Triangular shaped proximal phalanges of the hand
Triangular shaped distal phalanges of the hand
Abnormal B cell subset distribution
nodes.def: Abnormal increase or decrease of any B cell subpopulation, measured as percentage of total CD19+ or CD20+ B cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

nodes.label: Anterior chamber cells
nodes.def: Tiny deposits corresponding to cells floating in the anterior chamber of the eye. This appearance is typically associated with intraocular inflammation leading to breakdown of the blood-aqueous barrier and resulting in an increase in the number of cells and in the aqueous humor. Grading (SUN Working Group) is performed by estimating the number of cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.

nodes.label: Cholangitis
nodes.def: Inflammation of the biliary ductal system, affecting the intrahepatic or extrahepatic portions, or both.

nodes.label: Abnormal vascular physiology
nodes.def: Abnormality of vascular function.

nodes.label: Abnormal ocular adnexa morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of the adjacent structures (i.e., adnexa) of the eye, defined as the lacrimal apparatus, the extraocular muscles and the eyelids, eyelashes, eyebrows and the conjunctiva.

nodes.label: Glomerular deposits
nodes.def: An abnormal accumulation of protein in the glomerulus.

nodes.label: Abnormal pulmonary vein morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the structure of the pulmonary veins.

nodes.label: Impairment of activities of daily living
nodes.def: Difficulty in performing one or more activities normally performed every day, such as eating, bathing, dressing, grooming, work, homemaking, and leisure.

nodes.label: Abnormal Bowman capsule morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of the double-walled capsule (Bowman capsule) that opens into a renal tubule.

nodes.label: Abnormal respiratory system morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of the respiratory system.

nodes.label: Pulmonary opacity
nodes.def: Opacity refers to any area that preferentially attenuates the x-ray beam and therefore appears more opaque than the surrounding area. It is a nonspecific term that does not indicate the size or pathologic nature of the abnormality.

nodes.label: Impairment in personality functioning
nodes.def: A maladaptive personality trait characterized by moderate or greater impairment in personality (self /interpersonal) functioning.

nodes.label: Orbital cleft
nodes.def: A facial cleft characterized by involvement of the orbit.

nodes.label: Abnormal P wave
nodes.def: Any anomaly of the P wave of the EKG, which results from atrial depolarization. The P wave occurs when the sinoatrial node creates an action potential that depolarizes the atria.

nodes.label: Weakness of facial musculature
nodes.def: Reduced strength of one or more muscles innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).

nodes.label: Lymphangiectasis
nodes.def: Dilation of the lymphatic vessels, the basic process that may result in the formation of a lymphangioma.

nodes.label: Bloodstream infectious agent
nodes.def: The presence of an infectious agent in the blood circulation.

nodes.label: Abnormal cranial nerve physiology
nodes.def: A functional abnormality affecting one or more of the cranial nerves, which emerge directly from the brain stem.

nodes.label: Abnormal portal venous system morphology
nodes.def: Any structural anomaly of the portal venous system, which comprises all of the veins draining the abdominal part of the digestive tract, including the lower esophagus but excluding the lower anal canal. The portal vein conveys blood from viscera and ramifies like an artery at the liver, ending at the sinusoids. Tributaries of the portal vein, which make up the portal venous system, are the splenic, superior mesenteric, left gastric, right gastric, paraumbilical, and cystic veins.

nodes.label: Heterotropia
nodes.def: Manifest deviation of the visual axes not controlled by fusion.

nodes.label: Abnormal sputum
nodes.def: Abnormal appearance of material expectorated (coughed up) from the respiratory system and that is composed of mucus but may contain other substances such as pus, blood, microorganisms, and fibrin.

nodes.label: Gastrointestinal eosinophilia
nodes.def: Eosinophilic infiltration of one or more gastrointestinal organs. Gastrointestinal eosinophilia is a broad term for abnormal eosinophil accumulation in the GI tract, involving many different disease identities. These diseases include primary eosinophil associated gastrointestinal diseases, gastrointestinal eosinophilia in HES and all gastrointestinal eosinophilic states associated with known causes. Each of these diseases has its unique features but there is no absolute boundary between them.

nodes.label: Abnormal urine cytology
nodes.def: An anomalous finding in the examination of the urine for cells.

nodes.label: Cough
nodes.def: A sudden, audible expulsion of air from the lungs through a partially closed glottis, preceded by inhalation.

nodes.label: Subcortical heterotopia
nodes.def: A form of heterotopia were the mislocalized gray matter is located deep within the white matter.

nodes.label: Abnormal platelet function
nodes.def: Any anomaly in the function of thrombocytes.

nodes.label: Hemorrhage of the eye
nodes.def: Bleeding from vessels of the various tissues of the eye.

nodes.label: Focal aware non-motor seizure
nodes.def: A focal non-motor seizure in which awareness is retained throughout the seizure.

nodes.label: Focal impaired awareness non-motor seizure
nodes.def: A focal non-motor seizure characterized by impaired awareness at some point during the seizure.

nodes.label: Increased fecal porphyrin
nodes.def: Abnormally high concentration of fecal porphyrins in feces.

nodes.label: Abnormal shoulder physiology
nodes.def: Anopmalous function of the shoulder. The shoulder is a ball-and-socket joint that is made up of humerus, scapula and clavicle, which are connected by the sternoclavicular joint (SC), the acromioclavicular joint (AC), the glenohumeral joint (GH), and the scapulothoracic joint (ST). The GH, AC and SC joints link the upper extremity to the axial skeleton at the thorax and enable movement at the shoulder joint: flexion, extension, and rotation of the arm.

nodes.label: Abnormal pulmonary alveolar system morphology
nodes.def: A structural abnormality of the pulmonary acinus, alveolar parenchyma, or alveoli.

nodes.label: Acute phase response
nodes.def: Presence of one or more manifestations of the acute phase response. Acute phase proteins (APP) are blood proteins primarily synthesized by hepatocytes as part of the acute phase response (APR). The APR is part of the early-defense or innate immune system, which is triggered by different stimuli including trauma, infection, stress, neoplasia, and inflammation. The APR results in a complex systemic reaction with the goal of reestablishing homeostasis and promoting healing.

nodes.label: Extractable nuclear antigen positivity
nodes.def: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against extractable nuclear components that are referred to as extractable because they can be extracted from cell nuclei with saline solution.

nodes.label: Addictive substance use
nodes.def: Chronic compulsive drug seeking and continued use despite harmful consequences.

nodes.label: Opportunistic fungal infection
nodes.def: An infection that is caused by a fungus that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such fungi take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.

nodes.label: Abnormal lymphocyte count
nodes.def: Any abnormality in the total number of lymphocytes in the blood.

nodes.label: Abnormal CSF pterin concentration
nodes.def: Abnormal concentration of a pterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

nodes.label: Neoplasm of the central nervous system
nodes.def: A neoplasm of the central nervous system.

nodes.label: Neoplasm of the eye
nodes.def: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the eye.

nodes.label: Muscle fiber cytoplasmatic inclusion bodies
nodes.def: The presence of inclusion bodies within the cytoplasm of muscle cells. Inclusion bodies are aggregates (deposits) or stainable material, usually misfolded proteins.

nodes.label: Juvenile aseptic necrosis
nodes.def: Juvenile aseptic necrosis comprises a group of orthopedic diseases characterized by interruption of the blood supply of a bone, followed by localized bony necrosis most often of the epiphyses of bones of children or teenagers.

nodes.label: Immunologic hypersensitivity
nodes.def: Immunological states where the immune system produces harmful responses upon reexposure to sensitizing antigens.

nodes.label: Upper-limb joint contracture
nodes.def: A limitation in the passive range of motion of a joint of the upper limb resulting from loss of elasticity in the periarticular tissues owing to structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules or skin.

nodes.label: Neoplasm of the large intestine
nodes.def: The presence of a neoplasm of the large intestine.

nodes.label: Abnormal palm morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the palm, that is, of the front of the hand.

nodes.label: Abnormality of globe location
nodes.def: An abnormality in the placement of the ocular globe (eyeball).

nodes.label: Sclerosis of 2nd finger phalanx
nodes.def: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the second finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

nodes.label: Sclerosis of 3rd finger phalanx
nodes.def: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the third finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

nodes.label: Sclerosis of 4th finger phalanx
nodes.def: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fourth finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

nodes.label: Sclerosis of 5th finger phalanx
nodes.def: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fifth finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

nodes.label: Sclerosis of proximal phalanx of toe
nodes.def: An elevation in bone density in one or more proximal phalanges of the toes. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

nodes.label: Frequency
nodes.def: Class to represent frequency of phenotypic abnormalities within a patient cohort.

nodes.label: Fractured distal finger phalanx
nodes.def: A partial or complete breakage of the distal phalanx of manus.

nodes.label: Toe phalanx fracture
nodes.def: A partial or complete breakage of the phalanx of pes.

nodes.label: Fractured finger phalanx
nodes.def: A partial or complete breakage of the phalanx of a finger.

nodes.label: Abnormal memory CD8+ T cell proportion
nodes.def: Abnormal increase or decrease of the memory CD8+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD45RA-, CD45RO+, or CD27-, measured as percentage of total CD8+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

nodes.label: Abnormality of musculature of soft palate
nodes.def: An abnormality of one or more of the five muscles of the soft palate.

nodes.label: Small joint hypermobilty
nodes.def:
The capability that a small joint (or a group of joints) has to move, passively and/or actively, beyond normal limits along physiological axes. Small joints include metacarpophalangeal joints, proximal interphalangeal joints, 
second to fifth metatarsophalangeal joints, and wrists.

nodes.label: Bloodstream pathogen-specific antibody positivity
nodes.def: Positive serology for a exposure to an infectious agent (i.e., examining serum for the presence of pathogen-specific antibodies).

nodes.label: Sputum infectious agent
nodes.def: The presence of an infectious agent in the sputum, as characterized by sputum culture or other investigation.

nodes.label: Brain localization
nodes.def: The pattern by which a phenotype is localized to or predominant in a part of the brain.

nodes.label: CSF pathogen-specific antibody positivity
nodes.def: Positive serology in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) for a exposure to an infectious agent (i.e., examining CSF for the presence of pathogen-specific antibodies).

nodes.label: Food allergy
nodes.def: Primary food allergies primarily occur as a result (most likely) of gastrointestinal sensitization to predominantly stable food allergens (glycoproteins). A secondary food allergy develops after primary sensitization to airborne allergens (e. g., pollen allergens) with subsequent reactions (due to cross-reactivity) to structurally related often labile allergens in (plant) foods.

nodes.label: Rhabdoid tumor
nodes.def: Rhabdoid tumors are rare aggressive malignancies in infants and young children with a poor prognosis. The most common anatomic localizations are the central nervous system, the kidneys, and other soft tissues.

nodes.label: Abnormal liver metabolite concentration
nodes.def: The concentration of a metabolite in the liver is above or below the limits of normal.

nodes.label: Shoulder contracture
nodes.def: Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of the shoulder joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin.

nodes.label: Involuntary vocalization
nodes.def: Production of sound done without will or conscious control. Involuntary vocalizations include tics, stereotypies vocalizations as part of dystonia or chorea, continuous vocalizing behaviors such as groaning or grunting, pathological laughter and crying, and others. These vocalizations are not recognized as socially or culturally appropriate.

nodes.label: Amplification of social interactions
nodes.def: A increase in the tendency of a person to seek or maintain social connections or interactions with others compared to previous norms for an individual.

nodes.label: Abnormal movement during sleep
nodes.def: Periodic Limb Movement Disorder, also known as Sleep-Related Myoclonus Syndrome or Nocturnal Myoclonus Syndrome, refers to the periodic and stereotypic movements of the legs or upper limbs during sleep.

nodes.label: Abnormal experience of reality
nodes.def: Subjective phenomena or perceptions that deviate from what is considered correct or are outside the range of normal human experiences.

nodes.label: Atherosclerotic lesion
nodes.def: A lesion associated with atherosclerosis, a multifactorial and multipart progressive disease manifested by the focal development within the arterial wall of lesions, that ranges from the development of a fatty streak, plaque progression, and plaque disruption. Atherosclerotic lesions demonstrate consistent morphological characteristics, which indicate that each type may stabilize temporarily or permanently and that progression to the next type may require an additional stimulus.

nodes.label: Opportunistic infection
nodes.def: An infection that is caused by a pathogen that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such pathogens take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.

nodes.label: Abnormal ear physiology
nodes.def: Any functional anomaly of the ear.

nodes.label: Compensatory head posture
nodes.def: A compensatory head posture occurs when the head is deviated out of the normal primary straight head position in order to compensate for an ocular problem.

nodes.label: Lupus nephritis
nodes.def: Lupus nephritis is a type of glomerulonephritis that constitutes one of the most severe organ manifestations of systemic lupus erythematosus. Lupus nephritis is subclassified in six distinct classes, that represent different manifestations and severities of renal involvement and guide the therapeutic management.

nodes.label: Blistering by anatomical location
nodes.def: Blistering (presence of multiple fluid filled blisters) categorized according to the body site where they occur.

nodes.label: Abnormal epidermis stratum granulosum morphology
nodes.def: An abnormal structure of the stratum granulosum, which is is a thin layer of cells in the epidermis lying above the stratum spinosum and below the stratum corneum.

nodes.label: Abnormal renal vascular morphology
nodes.def: Anomalous structure of a blood vessel in the kidney.

nodes.label: Abnormality of vitamin metabolism
nodes.def: An anomaly in the metabolism of a vitamin.

nodes.label: Abnormal glial cell morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the glia cell.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the tonsils
nodes.def: An abnormality of the tonsils.

nodes.label: Neoplasm of the small intestine
nodes.def: The presence of a neoplasm of the small intestine.

nodes.label: Abnormal morphology of female internal genitalia
nodes.def: An abnormality of the female internal genitalia.

nodes.label: Ambiguous genitalia
nodes.def: A genital phenotype that is not clearly assignable to a single gender. Ambiguous genitalia can be evaluated using the Prader scale: Prader 0: Normal female external genitalia. Prader 1: Female external genitalia with clitoromegaly. Prader 2: Clitoromegaly with partial labial fusion forming a funnel-shaped urogenital sinus. Prader 3: Increased phallic enlargement. Complete labioscrotal fusion forming a urogenital sinus with a single opening. Prader 4: Complete scrotal fusion with urogenital opening at the base or on the shaft of the phallus. Prader 5: Normal male external genitalia. The diagnosis of ambiguous genitalia is made for Prader 1-4.

nodes.label: Vesicoureteral reflux
nodes.def: Abnormal (retrograde) movement of urine from the bladder into ureters or kidneys related to inadequacy of the valvular mechanism at the ureterovesicular junction or other causes.

nodes.label: Tall stature
nodes.def: A height above that which is expected according to age and gender norms.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the genitourinary system
nodes.def: The presence of any abnormality of the genitourinary system.

nodes.label: Hypogonadism
nodes.def: A decreased functionality of the gonad.

nodes.label: Cleft soft palate
nodes.def: Cleft of the soft palate (also known as the velum, or muscular palate) as a result of a developmental defect occurring between the 7th and 12th week of pregnancy. Cleft soft palate can cause functional abnormalities of the Eustachian tube with resulting middle ear anomalies and hearing difficulties, as well as speech problems associated with hypernasal speech due to velopharyngeal insufficiency.

nodes.label: Abnormal oral frenulum morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the lingual frenulum, that is of the small fold of mucous membrane that attaches the tongue to the floor of the mouth, or the presence of accessory frenula in the oral cavity.

nodes.label: Oral cavity telangiectasia
nodes.def: Presence of telangiectases in the oral cavity.

nodes.label: Hydrocephalus
nodes.def: Hydrocephalus is an active distension of the ventricular system of the brain resulting from inadequate passage of CSF from its point of production within the cerebral ventricles to its point of absorption into the systemic circulation.

nodes.label: Facial asymmetry
nodes.def: An abnormal difference between the left and right sides of the face.

nodes.label: Abnormal auditory canal morphology
nodes.def: Any structural abnormality of the external acoustic tube (also known as the auditory canal).

nodes.label: Retinal detachment
nodes.def: Separation of the inner layers of the retina (neural retina) from the pigment epithelium.

nodes.label: Myopia
nodes.def: An abnormality of refraction characterized by the ability to see objects nearby clearly, while objects in the distance appear blurry.

nodes.label: Retinal degeneration
nodes.def: A nonspecific term denoting degeneration of the retinal pigment epithelium and/or retinal photoreceptor cells.

nodes.label: Abnormal uvea morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the uvea, the vascular layer of the eyeball.

nodes.label: Ophthalmoparesis
nodes.def: Ophthalmoplegia is a paralysis or weakness of one or more of the muscles that control eye movement.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the frontal hairline
nodes.def: An anomaly in the placement or shape of the hairline (trichion) on the forehead, that is, the border between skin on the forehead that has head hair and that does not.

nodes.label: Periodontitis
nodes.def: Inflammation of the periodontium.

nodes.label: Motor stereotypy
nodes.def: Use of the same abnormal action in response to certain triggers or at random. They may be used as a way to regulate one's internal state but must otherwise have no apparent functional purpose.

nodes.label: Anxiety
nodes.def: Intense feelings of nervousness, tension, or panic often arise in response to interpersonal stresses. There is worry about the negative effects of past unpleasant experiences and future negative possibilities. Individuals may feel fearful, apprehensive, or threatened by uncertainty, and they may also have fears of falling apart or losing control.

nodes.label: Delayed speech and language development
nodes.def: A degree of language development that is significantly below the norm for a child of a specified age.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the diaphragm
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the diaphragm, the sheet of skeletal muscle that separates the thoracic cavity from the abdominal cavity.

nodes.label: Oligozoospermia
nodes.def: Reduced count of spermatozoa in the semen, defined as a sperm count below 20 million per milliliter semen.

nodes.label: Hyperthyroidism
nodes.def: An abnormality of thyroid physiology characterized by excessive secretion of the thyroid hormones thyroxine (i.e., T4) and/or 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine zwitterion (i.e., triiodothyronine or T3).

nodes.label: Atypical scarring of skin
nodes.def: Atypically scarred skin .

nodes.label: Cutaneous photosensitivity
nodes.def: An increased sensitivity of the skin to light. Photosensitivity may result in a rash upon exposure to the sun (which is known as photodermatosis). Photosensitivity can be diagnosed by phototests in which light is shone on small areas of skin.

nodes.label: Melanocytic nevus
nodes.def: A oval and round, colored (usually medium-to dark brown, reddish brown, or flesh colored) lesion. Typically, a melanocytic nevus is less than 6 mm in diameter, but may be much smaller or larger.

nodes.label: Multiple lipomas
nodes.def: The presence of multiple lipomas (a type of benign tissue made of fatty tissue).

nodes.label: Angiokeratoma
nodes.def: Angiokeratomas are hyperkeratotic papules that are characterized histologically by superficial ectatic (i.e., dilated) blood vessels with epidermal proliferation. Clinically, angiokeratoma presents as a small, raised, dark-red spot.

nodes.label: Prominent superficial veins
nodes.def: A condition in which superficial veins (i.e., veins just under the skin) are more conspicuous or noticeable than normal.

nodes.label: Visual impairment
nodes.def: Visual impairment (or vision impairment) is vision loss (of a person) to such a degree as to qualify as an additional support need through a significant limitation of visual capability resulting from either disease, trauma, or congenital or degenerative conditions that cannot be corrected by conventional means, such as refractive correction, medication, or surgery.

nodes.label: Ptosis
nodes.def: The upper eyelid margin is positioned 3 mm or more lower than usual and covers the superior portion of the iris (objective); or, the upper lid margin obscures at least part of the pupil (subjective).

nodes.label: Abnormal heart valve morphology
nodes.def: Any structural abnormality of a cardiac valve.

nodes.label: Coronary artery atherosclerosis
nodes.def: Reduction of the diameter of the coronary arteries as the result of an accumulation of atheromatous plaques within the walls of the coronary arteries, which increases the risk of myocardial ischemia.

nodes.label: Atrioventricular block
nodes.def: Delayed or lack of conduction of atrial depolarizations through the atrioventricular node to the ventricles.

nodes.label: Ectopia cordis
nodes.def: Congenital malformation of the ventral wall with partial or total evisceration of the heart outside the thoracic cavity and through the defect in the ventral wall.

nodes.label: Pancreatitis
nodes.def: The presence of inflammation in the pancreas.

nodes.label: Camptodactyly of toe
nodes.def: Camptodactyly is a painless flexion contracture of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint that is usually gradually progressive. This term refers to camptodactyly of one or more toes.

nodes.label: Broad toe
nodes.def: Visible increase in width of the non-hallux digit without an increase in the dorso-ventral dimension.

nodes.label: Decreased total neutrophil count
nodes.def: Abnormal decrease of absolute number of neutrophils in the blood, per microlitre, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

nodes.label: Abnormal leukocyte morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of leukocytes.

nodes.label: Thromboembolism
nodes.def: The formation of a blood clot inside a blood vessel that subsequently travels through the blood stream from the site where it formed to another location in the body, generally leading to vascular occlusion at the distant site.

nodes.label: Abnormal granulocyte morphology
nodes.def: Any structural abnormality or abnormal count of granulocytes.

nodes.label: Fever
nodes.def: Body temperature elevated above the normal range.

nodes.label: Renal tubular acidosis
nodes.def: Acidosis owing to malfunction of the kidney tubules with accumulation of metabolic acids and hyperchloremia, potentially leading to complications including hypokalemia, hypercalcinuria, nephrolithiasis and nephrocalcinosis.

nodes.label: Abnormal tubulointerstitial morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality that involves the tubules and interstitial tissue of the kidney.

nodes.label: Tessier cleft
nodes.def: A congenital malformation with a cleft (gap or opening) in the face.

nodes.label: Vomiting
nodes.def: Forceful ejection of the contents of the stomach through the mouth by means of a series of involuntary spasmic contractions.

nodes.label: Abnormal lung lobation
nodes.def: A developmental defect in the formation of pulmonary lobes.

nodes.label: Apnea
nodes.def: Lack of breathing with no movement of the respiratory muscles and no exchange of air in the lungs. This term refers to a disposition to have recurrent episodes of apnea rather than to a single event.

nodes.label: Azotemia
nodes.def: An increased concentration of nitrogen compounds in the blood.

nodes.label: Pleural effusion
nodes.def: The presence of an excessive amount of fluid in the pleural cavity.

nodes.label: Focal clonic seizure
nodes.def: A focal clonic seizure is a type of focal motor seizure characterized by sustained rhythmic jerking, that is regularly repetitive.

nodes.label: Constriction of peripheral visual field
nodes.def: An absolute or relative decrease in retinal sensitivity extending from edge (periphery) of the visual field in a concentric pattern. The visual field is the area that is perceived simultaneously by a fixating eye.

nodes.label: Retinal exudate
nodes.def: Fluid which has escaped from retinal blood vessels with a high concentration of lipid, protein, and cellular debris with a typically bright, reflective, white or cream colored appearance on the surface of the retina.

nodes.label: Postaxial hand polydactyly
nodes.def: Supernumerary digits located at the ulnar side of the hand (that is, on the side with the fifth finger).

nodes.label: Mental deterioration
nodes.def: Loss of previously present mental abilities, generally in adults.

nodes.label: Holoprosencephaly
nodes.def: Holoprosencephaly is a structural anomaly of the brain in which the developing forebrain fails to divide into two separate hemispheres and ventricles.

nodes.label: Cholestasis
nodes.def: Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in bile ducts.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the shoulder girdle musculature
Abnormality of the musculature of the upper arm
Growth delay
nodes.def: A deficiency or slowing down of growth pre- and postnatally.

nodes.label: Obesity
nodes.def: Accumulation of substantial excess body fat.

nodes.label: Ascites
nodes.def: Accumulation of fluid in the peritoneal cavity (between the layers of the peritoneum that lines the abdomen).

nodes.label: Alopecia
nodes.def: A noncongenital process of hair loss, which may progress to partial or complete baldness.

nodes.label: Premature birth
nodes.def: The birth of a baby of less than 37 weeks of gestational age.

nodes.label: Tetralogy of Fallot
nodes.def: A congenital cardiac malformation comprising pulmonary stenosis, overriding aorta, ventricular septum defect, and right ventricular hypertrophy. The diagnosis of TOF is made if at least three of the four above mentioned features are present.

nodes.label: Abnormal aortic valve morphology
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the aortic valve.

nodes.label: Tachycardia
nodes.def: A rapid heartrate that exceeds the range of the normal resting heartrate for age.

nodes.label: Congenital contracture
nodes.def: One or more flexion contractures (a bent joint that cannot be straightened actively or passively) that are present at birth.

nodes.label: Abnormality of radial diaphysis
nodes.def: An anomaly of the radial diaphysis.

nodes.label: Sclerosis of hand bone
nodes.def: Osteosclerosis affecting one or more bones of the hand.

nodes.label: Curved phalanges of the 5th finger
nodes.def: Curved phalanges of the 5th (little) finger.

nodes.label: Abnormal scaphoid morphology
nodes.def: Any structural anomaly of the scaphoid. The scaphoid is the largest bone of the proximal row of carpal bones. It is located on the same side as the thumb.

nodes.label: Abnormal lunate bone morphology
nodes.def: Any structural anomaly of the lunate bone, which is located in the proximal row of carpal bones.

nodes.label: Abnormality of body weight
nodes.def: An abnormal increase or decrease of weight or an abnormal distribution of mass in the body.

nodes.label: Weakness of muscles of respiration
nodes.def: Reduced function of the muscles required to generate subatmospheric pressure in the thoracic cavity during breathing: the diaphragm, the external intercostal and the interchondral part of the internal intercostal muscles.

nodes.label: Abnormality of bone mineral density
nodes.def: This term applies to all changes in bone mineral density which (depending on severity) can be seen on x-rays as a change in density and or structure of the bone. Changes may affect all bones of the organism, just certain bones or only parts of bones and include decreased mineralisation as may be seen in osteoporosis or increased mineralisation and or ossification as in osteopetrosis, exostoses or any kind of atopic calicfications of different origin and distribution. The overall amount of mineralization of the bone-organ can be measured as the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones, usually measured by densitometry of the lumbar spine or hip. The measurements are usually reported as g/cm3 or as a Z-score (the number of standard deviations above or below the mean for the patient's age and sex). Note that measurement with this method does not reflect local changes in other bones, and as such might not be correct with regard the hole bone-organ.

nodes.label: Abnormal enteric ganglion morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the enteric nervous system, which comprises two types of ganglia, the myenteric (Auerbach's) and submucosal (Meissner's) plexuses. The enteric nervous system functions to control gut movement, fluid exchange between the gut and its lumen, and local blood flow.

nodes.label: Gastrointestinal inflammation
nodes.def: Inflammation of the alimentary part of the gastrointestinal system.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the sense of smell
nodes.def: An anomaly in the ability to perceive and distinguish scents (odors).

nodes.label: Cranial hyperostosis
nodes.def: Excessive growth of the bones of cranium, i.e., of the skull.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the middle ear ossicles
nodes.def: An abnormality of the middle-ear ossicles (three small bones called malleus, incus, and stapes) that are contained within the middle ear and serve to transmit sounds from the air to the fluid-filled labyrinth (cochlea).

nodes.label: Absent or minimally ossified vertebral bodies
Decreased facial expression
nodes.def: A reduced degree of voluntary and involuntary facial movements involved in responded to others or expressing emotions.

nodes.label: Venous thrombosis
nodes.def: Formation of a blood clot (thrombus) inside a vein, causing the obstruction of blood flow.

nodes.label: Abnormal T cell morphology
nodes.def: Abnormal increase or decrease of total or subset T cell count. T cells are commonly characterized as CD3+ lymphocytes, or their subpopulations, in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group, measured ex vivo. These may include both TCR alpha/beta and gamma/delta T cells.

nodes.label: Meningioma
nodes.def: The presence of a meningioma, i.e., a benign tumor originating from the dura mater or arachnoid mater.

nodes.label: Thyroid carcinoma
nodes.def: The presence of a carcinoma of the thyroid gland.

nodes.label: Hyperbilirubinemia
nodes.def: An increased amount of bilirubin in the blood.

nodes.label: Neuroblastoma
nodes.def: Neuroblastoma is a solid tumor that originate in neural crest cells of the sympathetic nervous system. Most neuroblastomas originate in the abdomen, and most abdominal neuroblastomas originate in the adrenal gland. Neuroblastomas can also originate in the thorax, usually in the posterior mediastinum.

nodes.label: Flattened epiphysis
nodes.def: Abnormal flatness (decreased height) of epiphyses.

nodes.label: Abnormal blood ion concentration
nodes.def: Abnormality of the homeostasis (concentration) of a monoatomic ion.

nodes.label: Increased circulating cortisol level
nodes.def: Overproduction of the hormone of cortisol by the adrenal cortex, resulting in a characteristic combination of clinical symptoms termed Cushing syndrome, with truncal obesity, a round, full face, striae atrophicae and acne, muscle weakness, and other features.

nodes.label: Rhabdomyolysis
nodes.def: Breakdown of muscle fibers that leads to the release of muscle fiber contents (myoglobin) into the bloodstream.

nodes.label: Abnormality of DNA repair
nodes.def: An abnormality of the process of DNA repair, that is, of the process of restoring DNA after damage.

nodes.label: Abnormality of complement system
nodes.def: An abnormality of the complement system.

nodes.label: Abnormal B cell physiology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the physiological functioning of B cells.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the metopic suture
nodes.def: The frontal suture divides the two halves of the frontal bone of the skull in infants and children and generally undergoes fusion by the age of six. A persistent frontal suture is referred to as a "metopic suture".

nodes.label: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the femur
nodes.def: Absence or underdevelopment of the femur.

nodes.label: Broad long bones
nodes.def: Increased cross-section (diameter) of the long bones. Note that widening may primarily affect specific regions of long bones (e.g., diaphysis or metaphysis), but this should be coded separately.

nodes.label: Metaphyseal enchondromatosis
nodes.def: An enchondroma is a benign growth of cartilage that develops within the medullary cavity of bone. Enchondromatosis refers to the presence of multiple enchondromas, and this term refers to the presence of multiple enchondromas within the medulla of metaphyseal bone. Radiographically an enchondroma presents a an oval, linear, or pyramidal osteolytic (radiolucent) lesion with well defined margins.

nodes.label: Intestinal polyp
nodes.def: A discrete abnormal tissue mass that protrudes into the lumen of the intestine and is attached to the intestinal wall either by a stalk, pedunculus, or a broad base.

nodes.label: Increased density of long bones
nodes.def: An abnormal increase in the bone density of the long bones.

nodes.label: Limited shoulder movement
nodes.def: A limitation of the range of movement of the shoulder joint.

nodes.label: Agenesis of incisor
nodes.def: Agenesis of incisor.

nodes.label: Abnormal femoral epiphysis morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of a growth plate of a femur.

nodes.label: Abnormal lower limb epiphysis morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of one or more epiphyses of one or both legs.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the clavicles
nodes.def: Absence or underdevelopment of the clavicles (collar bones).

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving bones of the thorax
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the cerebellar vermis
nodes.def: Absence or underdevelopment of the vermis of cerebellum.

nodes.label: Hypointensity of cerebral white matter on MRI
nodes.def: A darker than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter.

nodes.label: Abnormal septum pellucidum morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the septum pellucidum, which is a thin, triangular, vertical membrane separating the lateral ventricles of the brain.

nodes.label: Abnormal choroid plexus morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the choroid plexus, which is the area in the cerebral ventricles in which cerebrospinal fluid is produced by modified ependymal cells.

nodes.label: Abnormal dermatoglyphics
nodes.def: An abnormality of dermatoglyphs (fingerprints), which are present on fingers, palms, toes, and soles.

nodes.label: Action tremor
nodes.def: A tremor present when the limbs are active, either when outstretched in a certain position or throughout a voluntary movement.

nodes.label: Leukoencephalopathy
nodes.def: This term describes abnormality of the white matter of the cerebrum resulting from damage to the myelin sheaths of nerve cells.

nodes.label: Abnormal midbrain morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the midbrain, which has as its parts the tectum, cerebral peduncle, midbrain tegmentum and cerebral aqueduct.

nodes.label: Abnormal motor neuron morphology
nodes.def: Any structural anomaly that affects the motor neuron.

nodes.label: Language impairment
nodes.def: Language impairment is a deficit in comprehension or production of language that includes reduced vocabulary, limited sentence structure, or impairments in written or spoken communication. Language abilities are substantially and quantifiably below age expectations.

nodes.label: Abnormal periventricular white matter morphology
nodes.def: A structural abnormality of the myelinated axons (white matter) located near the cerebral ventricles.

nodes.label: Abnormal cortical gyration
nodes.def: An abnormality of the gyri (i.e., the ridges) of the cerebral cortex of the brain.

nodes.label: Colitis
nodes.def: Colitis refers to an inflammation of the colon and is often used to describe an inflammation of the large intestine (colon, cecum and rectum). Colitides may be acute and self-limited or chronic, and broadly fit into the category of digestive diseases.

nodes.label: Scoliosis
nodes.def: The presence of an abnormal lateral curvature of the spine.

nodes.label: Increased susceptibility to fractures
nodes.def: An abnormally increased tendency to fractures of bones caused by an abnormal reduction in bone strength that is generally associated with an increased risk of fracture.

nodes.label: Abnormal sella turcica morphology
nodes.def: Abnormality of the sella turcica, a saddle-shaped depression in the sphenoid bone at the base of the human skull.

nodes.label: Osteomyelitis
nodes.def: Osteomyelitis is an inflammatory process accompanied by bone destruction and caused by an infecting microorganism.

nodes.label: Vertebral wedging
nodes.def: An abnormal shape of the vertebral bodies whereby the vertebral bodies are thick on one side and taper to a thin edge at the other.

nodes.label: Vertebral arch anomaly
nodes.def: A morphological abnormality of the vertebral arch, i.e., of the posterior part of a vertebra.

nodes.label: Aminoaciduria
nodes.def: An increased concentration of an amino acid in the urine.

nodes.label: Muscle spasm
nodes.def: Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles.

nodes.label: Elevated circulating long chain fatty acid concentration
nodes.def: Increased concentration of long-chain fatty acids in the blood circulation.

nodes.label: Disproportionate short-trunk short stature
nodes.def: A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs.

nodes.label: Muscle stiffness
nodes.def: A condition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm.

nodes.label: Limb muscle weakness
nodes.def: Reduced strength and weakness of the muscles of the arms and legs.

nodes.label: Proximal muscle weakness
nodes.def: A lack of strength of the proximal muscles.

nodes.label: Irregular epiphyses of the upper limbs
Feeding difficulties in infancy
nodes.def: Impaired feeding performance of an infant as manifested by difficulties such as weak and ineffective sucking, brief bursts of sucking, and falling asleep during sucking. There may be difficulties with chewing or maintaining attention.

nodes.label: Adipose tissue loss
nodes.def: A reduction in the amount of adipose tissue (fat) compared with the amount previously present in an individual.

nodes.label: Rhizomelia
nodes.def: Disproportionate shortening of the proximal segment of limbs (i.e. the femur and humerus).

nodes.label: Decreased activity of mitochondrial respiratory chain
nodes.def: Decreased activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain.

nodes.label: Hypoplasia of the musculature
nodes.def: Underdevelopment of the musculature.

nodes.label: Airway obstruction
nodes.def: Obstruction of conducting airways of the lung.

nodes.label: Curved phalanges of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: Curved appearance of the phalanges of the 3rd finger.

nodes.label: Ivory epiphyses of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Sclerosis of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

nodes.label: Retinal hamartoma
nodes.def: A hamartoma (a benign, focal malformation consisting of a disorganized mixture of cells and tissues) of the retina.

nodes.label: Thumb contracture
nodes.def: Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of the thumb joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin. The term camptodactyly is used if the distal and/or proximal interphalangeal joints are affected.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the thumb
Short phalanx of finger
nodes.def: Short (hypoplastic) phalanx of finger, affecting one or more phalanges.

nodes.label: Tooth agenesis
nodes.def: The absence of one or more teeth from the normal series by a failure to develop

nodes.label: Forearm undergrowth
nodes.def: Forearm shortening because of underdevelopment of one or more bones of the forearm.

nodes.label: Vitreoretinopathy
nodes.def: Ocular abnormality characterized by premature degeneration of the vitreous and the retina that may be associated with increased risk of retinal detachment.

nodes.label: Corneal opacity
nodes.def: A reduction of corneal clarity.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the vasculature of the eye
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the lens
nodes.def: Absence or underdevelopment of the lens.

nodes.label: Abnormal antitragus morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the antitragus, which is a small tubercle opposite to the tragus of the ear. The antitragus and the tragus are separated by the intertragic notch.

nodes.label: Abnormal columella morphology
nodes.def: A structural abnormality of the columella.

nodes.label: Duplication of thumb phalanx
nodes.def: Complete or partial duplication of the phalanges of the thumb. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx), a partially fused appearance of the two bones (bifid), two separate bones appearing side to side, or completely duplicated phalanges (proximal and distal phalanx of the thumb and/or 1st metacarpal). In contrast to the phalanges of the digits 2-5 (proximal, middle and distal), the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

nodes.label: Aplasia of metacarpal bones
nodes.def: Developmental defect associated with absence of one or more metacarpal bones.

nodes.label: Deviation of the hallux
nodes.def: Displacement of the big toe from its normal position.

nodes.label: Patchy sclerosis of hallux phalanx
nodes.def: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more phalanges of the big toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

nodes.label: Duplication of phalanx of hallux
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of one or more phalanx of big toe.

nodes.label: Duplication of phalanx of toe
nodes.def: Partial/complete duplication of one or more phalanx of toe.

nodes.label: Broad middle phalanges of the toes
Curved middle phalanx of toe
nodes.def: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more middle toe phalanges.

nodes.label: Aplasia/hypoplasia of proximal toe phalanx
nodes.def: Absence (agenesis) or underdevelopment of the proximal phalanx of the toe.

nodes.label: Enlarged epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Triangular epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the external ear
nodes.def: The presence of aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of all or part of the external ear.

nodes.label: Abnormal renal artery morphology
nodes.def: Any structural abnormality of the renal artery.

nodes.label: Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the toes
Skin dimple
nodes.def: Skin dimples are cutaneous indentations that are the result of tethering of the skin to underlying structures (bone) causing an indentation.

nodes.label: Abnormality of pain sensation
nodes.def: Pain is an unpleasant sensation that can range from mild, localized discomfort to agony, whereby the physical part of pain results from nerve stimulation and is often accompanied by an emotional component. This term groups abnormalities in pain sensation presumed to result from abnormalities related to the specific nerve fibers that carry the pain impulses to the brain.

nodes.label: EEG with spike-wave complexes
nodes.def: Complexes of spikes (<70 ms) and sharp waves (70-200 ms), which are sharp transient waves that have a strong association with epilepsy, in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating phenylalanine concentration
nodes.def: Any deviation from the normal concentration of phenylalanine in the blood circulation.

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating aspartate family amino acid concentration
nodes.def: Any deviation from the normal concentration of an aspartate family amino acid in the blood circulation.

nodes.label: Abnormal external nose morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the external nose.

nodes.label: Hyperlipoproteinemia
nodes.def: An abnormal increase in the level of lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

nodes.label: Abnormal cerebral subcortex morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the cerebral subcortex.

nodes.label: Misalignment of incisors
nodes.def: Misaligned incisor.

nodes.label: Abnormal hand epiphysis morphology
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the epiphyses of the phalanges or metacarpal bones.

nodes.label: Abnormal respiratory motile cilium morphology
nodes.def: Abnormal arrangement of the structures of the motile cilium.

nodes.label: EEG with constitutional variants
nodes.def: An EEG with constitutional variants contains waves that are rare or unusual but not generally pathologic.

nodes.label: EEG with focal sharp slow waves
nodes.def: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

nodes.label: EEG with focal sharp waves
nodes.def: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.

nodes.label: Unusual CNS infection
nodes.def: A type of infection of the central nervous system that can be regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection.

nodes.label: Abnormal lacrimal duct morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the lacrimal duct, a duct that drain tears from the conjunctiva, via the lacrimal puncta, into the lacrimal sac.

nodes.label: Abnormal Descemet membrane morphology
nodes.def: Abnormality of Descemet's membrane, which is the basement membrane of the corneal endothelium.

nodes.label: Abnormal corneal stroma morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the stroma of cornea, also known as the substantia propria of cornea.

nodes.label: Abnormal atrial arrangement
nodes.def: Abnormality of the spatial relationship of the atria to other components of the heart.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving bones of the skull
Osteolysis involving bones of the feet
Synostosis involving bones of the lower limbs
nodes.def: An abnormal union between bones or parts of bones lower limbs.

nodes.label: Synostosis involving bones of the feet
Curved phalanges of the 4th finger
nodes.def: Curved appearance of the phalanges of the 4th (ring) finger.

nodes.label: Ivory epiphyses of the 5th finger
nodes.def: Sclerosis of the epiphyses of the 5th finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

nodes.label: Ivory epiphyses of the 4th finger
nodes.def: Sclerosis of the epiphyses of the 4th finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

nodes.label: Ivory epiphyses of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: Sclerosis of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

nodes.label: Focal cognitive seizure with deja vu/jamais vu
nodes.def: A focal cognitive seizure characterized by memory phenomena such as feelings of familiarity (deja vu) and unfamiliarity (jamais vu) as the initial semiological manifestation.

nodes.label: Cutaneous melanoma
nodes.def: The presence of a melanoma of the skin.

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating corticosterone level
nodes.def: An abnormality of the concentration of corticosterone in the blood.

nodes.label: Abnormality of multiple cell lineages in the bone marrow
Hemophagocytosis
nodes.def: Phagocytosis by macrophages of erythrocytes, leukocytes, platelets, and their precursors in bone marrow and other tissues.

nodes.label: Craniofacial dystonia
nodes.def: A form of focal dystonia affecting the face and especially the jaw that is induced by the act of speaking. It is an involuntary contraction of the masticatory muscles, resulting in dysarthria or dysphagia.

nodes.label: Patchy sclerosis of 2nd toe phalanx
nodes.def: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the second toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

nodes.label: Patchy sclerosis of 3rd toe phalanx
nodes.def: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the third toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

nodes.label: Abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd toe
nodes.def: An anomaly of the proximal phalanx of third toe.

nodes.label: Patchy sclerosis of 4th toe phalanx
nodes.def: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the fourth toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the distal phalanx of the 4th toe
Abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the 4th toe
Patchy sclerosis of 5th toe phalanx
nodes.def: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the fifth toe. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the middle phalanx of the 5th toe
Abnormal morphology of the proximal phalanx of the 5th toe
Aplasia/hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe
nodes.def: Absence (agenesis) or underdevelopment of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd toe.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 2nd toe
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the 2nd toe
Aplasia of the phalanges of the 2nd toe
Short phalanx of the 2nd toe
nodes.def: Reduced length of one or more phalanx of second toe as a result of developmental hypoplasia.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the urachus
nodes.def: Abnormality of the urachus.

nodes.label: Cone-shaped epiphysis
nodes.def: Cone-shaped epiphyses (also known as coned epiphyses) are epiphyses that invaginate into cupped metaphyses. That is, the epiphysis has a cone-shaped distal extension resulting from increased growth of the central portion of the epiphysis relative to its periphery.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the distal femoral epiphysis
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the distal epiphysis of the femur.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the distal radial epiphysis
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the distal epiphysis of the radius.

nodes.label: Abnormal pituitary gland morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of the pituitary gland.

nodes.label: Laterality
nodes.def: The localization with respect to the side of the body of the specified phenotypic abnormality.

nodes.label: Abnormal male reproductive system physiology
nodes.def: An abnormal functionality of the male genital system.

nodes.label: Abnormal drug response
nodes.def: An anomalous response to a medication related to individual variation in metabolic or immune response to drugs varying from potentially from potentially life-threatening adverse drug reactions to alteration of therapeutic efficacy.

nodes.label: Abnormal cutaneous elastic fiber morphology
nodes.def: Any structural anomaly of the elastic fibers of the skin. Elastic fibers are the essential extracellular matrix macromolecules comprising an elastin core surrounded by a mantle of fibrillin-rich microfibrils.

nodes.label: Capillary malformation
nodes.def: A capillary malformation is a flat, sharply defined vascular stain of the skin. It may cover a large surface area or it may be scattered and appear as little islands of color. In a capillary maformation, the predominant vessels are small, slow-flow vessels (i.e., arterioles and postcapillary venules).

nodes.label: Abnormal hepatobiliary system physiology
nodes.def: A functional anomaly of the hepatobiliary system

nodes.label: Bullet-shaped proximal phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: Short and wide proximal phalanges that taper distally . Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

nodes.label: Osteolytic defects of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Patchy sclerosis of proximal phalanx of finger
nodes.def: Uneven increase in bone density of the proximal phalanges of the hand.

nodes.label: Symphalangism affecting the proximal phalanges of the hand
Abnormal morphology of the choroidal vasculature
Abnormal urinary mineral level
nodes.def: An abnormal concentration or amount of a mineral in the urine. Medically relevant minerals include calcium, phosphorus, potassium, sodium, chloride, magnesium, iron, zinc, iodine, chromium, copper, fluoride, molybdenum, manganese, and selenium.

nodes.label: Abnormal fetal skin morphology
nodes.def: Any structural anomaly of the skin of the fetus or newborn. Terms in this subhierarchy are restricted to findings that can only be observed in the prenatal period. Other HPO terms can also be used to describe fetal phenotypes.

nodes.label: Abnormal social development
nodes.def: A substantial lag in the ahcievement of or divergence from typical milestones in social interaction and communication skills. Social-emotional competencies in young children include helping, sharing, comforting, and exhibiting empathy and compliance.

nodes.label: Disordered formal thought process
nodes.def: An abnormality in the dynamic mode, rate, or form of thought processes as recognized from the flow of ideas expressed in speech. Successive thoughts and speech are easily diverted by external stimuli or internal superficial associations. Unable to maintain a constant train of thought and loose themselves in side issues, losing the thread and are unable to recover it. Superficial connections appear to drive the subject matter.

nodes.label: Abnormal preoccupation
nodes.def: Preoccupations refers to being absorbed in any particular thought, activity, or concern that captures the attention of the individual. It may have a positive or negative connotation.

nodes.label: Abnormal von Willebrand factor multimer distribution
nodes.def: Deviation from the normal von Willebrand factor multimer pattern.

nodes.label: Tremor by anatomical site
nodes.def: Tremor classified by the affected body part.

nodes.label: Abnormal coronary sinus morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the coronary sinus, which is formed by the union of the great cardiac vein and the left marginal vein and terminates in the right atrium. The coronary sinus functions to o collect deoxygenated blood from the myocardium of the heart and drain it into the right atrium.

nodes.label: Abnormal fundus autofluorescence imaging
nodes.def: Fundus autofluorescence (FAF) is a non-invasive retinal imaging modality used in clinical practice to provide a density map of lipofuscin, the predominant ocular fluorophore, in the retinal pigment epithelium. Autofluorescent patterns result from the complex interaction of fluorophores such a lipofuscin, which release an autofluorescent signal, and elements such as melanin and rhodopsin, which absorb the excitation beam and attenuate autofluorescence. Other structures such as retinal vessels and the crystalline lens may also influence autofluorescence through blocking and interference.

nodes.label: Sacrococcygeal teratoma
nodes.def: A teratoma arising in the sacro-coccygeal region.

nodes.label: Abnormal tongue physiology
nodes.def: Any functional anomaly of the tongue.

nodes.label: Knee pain
nodes.def: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the knee.

nodes.label: Hyperintensity of cerebral white matter on MRI
nodes.def: A brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter.

nodes.label: Abnormal morphology of the great vessels
nodes.def: A structural anomaly affecting a blood vessel involved in the circulation of the heart, i.e., the superior or inferior vena cava, the pulmonary arteries, the pulmonary veins, and the aorta.

nodes.label: Abnormal systemic blood pressure
nodes.def: A chronic deviation from normal pressure in the systemic arterial system.

nodes.label: Abnormal branching pattern of left aortic arch
nodes.def: A deviance from the norm of the origin or course of the right brachiocephalic artery, the left common carotid artery, the left subclavian artery or the proximal vertebral arteries, whereby the aortic arch descends on the left as normal (as opposed to right aortic arch).

nodes.label: Acellular urinary casts
nodes.def: A type of urinary cast composed of a proteinaceous matrix without a substantial number of cells.

nodes.label: Abnormal subclavian artery morphology
nodes.def: Any anomaly of a subclavian artery.

nodes.label: Abnormal hypothalamus physiology
nodes.def: An abnormal functionality of the hypothalamus.

nodes.label: Abnormal hypothalamus morphology
nodes.def: Any structural anomaly of the hypothalamus.

nodes.label: Abnormal aortic arch morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of the arch of aorta.

nodes.label: Abnormality of folate metabolism
nodes.def: An abnormality of the metabolism of folic acid, which is also known as vitamin B9.

nodes.label: Abnormal protein O-linked glycosylation
nodes.def: An anomaly of protein O-linked glycosylation, i.e., of the process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via the hydroxyl group of a serine or threonine residue.

nodes.label: Abnormal lymphocyte physiology
nodes.def: Any anomaly of lymphocyte function.

nodes.label: Restricted or repetitive behaviors or interests
nodes.def: A broad range of compulsive behaviors are repeated, including simple motor stereotypies and tics, as well as more complex repetitive movements or compulsions.

nodes.label: Soft tissue neoplasm
nodes.def: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) that arises from the soft tissue. The most common types are lipomatous (fatty), vascular, smooth muscle, fibrous, and fibrohistiocytic neoplasms.

nodes.label: Abnormal dermoepidermal junction morphology
nodes.def: Any anomaly of the structure of the acellular zone that is between the dermis and the epidermis and which functions to bind the epidermis to the dermis and to serve as a selective barrier allowing the control of molecular and cellular exchanges between the two compartments.

nodes.label: Abnormal aortic valve cusp morphology
nodes.def: Any structural anomaly of the aortic valve leaflets.

nodes.label: Large intestinal polyposis
nodes.def: The presence of multiple polyps in the large intestine.

nodes.label: Lower extremity joint dislocation
nodes.def: Displacement or malalignment of one or more joints in the lower extremity (leg).

nodes.label: Abnormal vertebral artery morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of the vertebral artery, the major artery of the neck that originates from the subclavian artery and merges to form the single midline basilar artery in a complex called the vertebrobasilar system.

nodes.label: Abnormal memory B cell proportion
nodes.def: A deviation of the normal proportion of memory B cells in circulation relative to total number of B cells. Memory B cells develop from naive B cells. Upon antigen rechallenge, memory B cells rapidly expand and differentiate into plasma cells under the cognate control of memory Th cells (Phase IV).

nodes.label: Vulvar neoplasm
nodes.def: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the female external genital tract (vulva).

nodes.label: Abnormal reflex
nodes.def: Any anomaly of a reflex, i.e., of an automatic response mediated by the nervous system (a reflex does not need the intervention of conscious thought to occur).

nodes.label: Presence of xenobiotic
nodes.def: Presence of a chemical substance found within an individual that is not naturally produced or expected to be present in human tissues or bodily fluids.

nodes.label: Abnormal eyelid physiology
nodes.def: Any functional abnormality of the eyelid.

nodes.label: Rosette
nodes.def: A halo or spoke-wheel arrangement of cells surrounding a central core or hub. The central hub may consist of an empty-appearing lumen or a space filled with cytoplasmic processes. The cytoplasm of each of the cells in the rosette is often wedge-shaped with the apex directed toward the central core; the nuclei of the cells participating in the rosette are peripherally positioned and form a ring or halo around the hub.

nodes.label: Increased vertical cup-to-disc ratio
nodes.def: An abnormal increase in the ratio of the height of the cup of the optic nerve head to the height of the disk.

nodes.label: Heterophoria
nodes.def: Heterophorias are latent deviations that are controlled by fusion. In certain circumstances (specific visual tasks, fatigue, illness, etc.), fusion can no longer be maintained and decompensation occurs.

nodes.label: Reduced contrast sensitivity
nodes.def: An abnormality in perception of contrast. Spatial contrast is a physical dimension referring to the light-dark transition of a border or an edge in an image that delineates the existence of a pattern or an object. Contrast sensitivity refers to a measure of how much contrast a person requires to see a target. Contrast-sensitivity measurements differ from acuity measurements; acuity is a measure of the spatial-resolving ability of the visual system under conditions of very high contrast, whereas contrast sensitivity is a measure of the threshold contrast for seeing a target.

nodes.label: Chronic kidney disease
nodes.def: Functional anomaly of the kidney persisting for at least three months.

nodes.label: Abnormal pineal morphology
nodes.def: A structural abnormality of the pineal gland.

nodes.label: Abnormal subarachnoid space morphology
nodes.def: Abnormality in the space in the meninges beneath the arachnoid membrane and above the pia mater that contains the cerebrospinal fluid.

nodes.label: Macule
nodes.def: A flat, distinct, discolored area of skin less than 1 cm wide that does not involve any change in the thickness or texture of the skin.

nodes.label: Neurodevelopmental abnormality
nodes.def: A deviation from normal of the neurological development of a child, which may include any or all of the aspects of the development of personal, social, gross or fine motor, and cognitive abilities.

nodes.label: Flexion contracture of finger
nodes.def: Chronic loss of joint motion in a finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

nodes.label: Severity
nodes.def: The intensity or degree of a manifestation.

nodes.label: Increased blood pressure
nodes.def: Abnormal increase in blood pressure. An individual measurement of increased blood pressure does not necessarily imply hypertension. In practical terms, multiple measurements are recommended to diagnose the presence of hypertension.

nodes.label: Acidemia
nodes.def: An abnormally low blood pH (usually defined as less than 7.35).

nodes.label: Abnormal HDL subfraction concentration
nodes.def: An abnormal concentration of an HDL subfraction, which can be determined by methods such as electrophoresis followed by densitometric determination of the areas under the peaks. Large HDL subfractions are defined as HDL1 (greater than 12 nm), HDL2b (9.7-12 nm), and HDL2a (8.8-9.69 nm). Small HDL subfractions are defined as HDL3a (8.2-8.79 nm), HDL3b (7.8-8.19 nm), and HDL3c (7.20-7.79 nm).

nodes.label: Abnormality of joint mobility
nodes.def: An abnormality in the range and ease of motion of joints across their normal range.

nodes.label: Neoplasm of the anterior pituitary
