nodes.def: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the adenohypophysis, which is also known as the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland.

nodes.label: Abnormal total T cell count
nodes.def: Abnormal increase or decrease of absolute number of T cells or of a subset of T cells, commonly characterized as CD3+ lymphocytes, in the blood, per microlitre, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These may include both TCR alpha/beta and gamma/delta T cells.

nodes.label: Abnormal bone ossification
nodes.def: Any anomaly in the formation of bone or of a bony substance, or the conversion of fibrous tissue or of cartilage into bone or a bony substance.

nodes.label: Abnormal sternal ossification
nodes.def: Any anomaly in the formation of the bony substance of the sternum.

nodes.label: Abnormal platelet count
nodes.def: Abnormal number of platelets per volume of blood. In a healthy adult, a normal platelet count is between 150,000 and 450,000 per microliter of blood.

nodes.label: Abnormality of circulating fibrinogen
nodes.def: An abnormality of the level of activity of circulating fibrinogen.

nodes.label: Abnormal metacarpophalangeal joint morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of a metacarpophalangeal joint.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the glenoid fossa
nodes.def: An anomaly of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.

nodes.label: Abnormal superior cerebellar peduncle morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of the superior cerebellar peduncle.

nodes.label: Abnormal pectoral muscle morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the pectoral muscle, comprising the pectoralis major, a thick, fan-shaped muscle of the anterior chest and the pectoralis minor, a thin, triangular muscle situated underneath the pectoralis major.

nodes.label: Ectopic ossification
nodes.def: Formation of abnormal, extraskeletal bony tissue, i.e., the presence of bone in soft tissue where bone normally does not exist.

nodes.label: Neonatal electro-clinical motor seizure
nodes.def: Neonatal electro-clinical motor seizure is a type of neonatal electro-clinical seizure with predominant motor features.

nodes.label: Abnormal bronchoalveolar lavage fluid morphology
nodes.def: Abnormal type or counts of nucleated immune cells and acellular components in bronchoalveolar lavage (BAL) fluid. BAL us performed with a fiberoptic bronchoscope in the wedged position within a selected bronchopulmonary segment. BAL is commonly used to inform the differential diagnosis of interstitial lung disease or to monitor therapeutic interventions.

nodes.label: Intracranial arterial calcification
nodes.def: An accumulation of calcium and phosphate in arteries with mineral deposits in the intimal or medial layer of the vessel wall in an artery that is located within the skull (intracranial).

nodes.label: Myocardial immune cell infiltration
nodes.def: An increase in the number of immune cells in myocardial tissue (which can be assumed to have migrated into the myocardium).

nodes.label: Abnormal CD8+ T cell proportion
nodes.def: Abnormal increase or decrease of cytotoxic CD3+CD8+ T cells, measured as percentage of total CD3+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group. These are usually measured within the TCR alpha/beta positive population.

nodes.label: Abnormal renal echogenicity
nodes.def: Anomalous echogenicity of the kidney on ultrasound examination.

nodes.label: Decreased circulating apolipoprotein concentration
nodes.def: Reduced concentration in the blood circulation of a lipid-transport protein (apoliprotein).

nodes.label: Increased circulating apolipoprotein circulation
nodes.def: Elevated concentration in the blood circulation of a lipid-transport protein (apoliprotein).

nodes.label: Interictal EEG abnormality
nodes.def: Interictal refers to a period of time between epileptic seizures. Electroencephalographic (EEG) patterns are important in the differential diagnosis of epilepsy, and the EEG is almost always abnormal during a seizure. Some persons with seizures may show EEG abnormalities between seizures, while others do not. In some cases, multiple interictal EEGs must be recorded before an abnormality is observed. In most cases the electrographic pattern of seizure onset is completely different from the activity recorded during interictal discharge.

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating beta globulin level
nodes.def: A deviation from the normal concentration of beta globulin. The beta globulins are a group of globular (globe-shaped) proteins in blood.

nodes.label: Abnormal fetal central nervous system morphology
nodes.def: An anomalous structural finding of the fetal central nervous system. Terms in this subhierarchy are restricted to findings that can only be observed in the prenatal period. Other HPO terms can also be used to describe fetal phenotypes.

nodes.label: Fetal intracranial hemorrhage
nodes.def: Abnormal bleeding inside the skull (cranium) of a fetus.

nodes.label: Abnormal fetal pulmonary morphology
nodes.def: An anomalous structural finding of the fetal lungs. Terms in this subhierarchy are restricted to findings that can only be observed in the prenatal period. Other HPO terms can also be used to describe fetal phenotypes.

nodes.label: Abnormal metabolism
nodes.def: An abnormality in the function of the chemical reactions related to processes including conversion of food to enter, synthesis of proteins, lipids, nucleic acids, and carbohydrates, or the elimination of waste products.

nodes.label: Positive urine infectious agent nucleic acid test
nodes.def: Detection of DNA and RNA originating from an infectious agent (bacteria, viruses, parasites and fungi) in the urine.

nodes.label: Digestive system neoplasm
nodes.def: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the digestive system.

nodes.label: Occupational exposure history
nodes.def: Exposure to a substance that results from the performance of an employee's duties.

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating creatine kinase concentration
nodes.def: Any deviation from the normal circulating creatine kinase concentration.

nodes.label: Abnormal tympanic membrane morphology
nodes.def: Any structural abnormality of the tympanic membrane

nodes.label: Past obstetric history
nodes.def: Information about past pregnancies including gravidity (number of times a woman has been pregnant, regardless of the outcome), parity (total number of births), gestational age of births, and medical conditions related to past pregnancies.

nodes.label: Abnormal pulse
nodes.def: An anomaly of the rhythmic throbbing of an artery that reflects the widening of the artery as blood flows through it and is caused by successive contractions of the heart.

nodes.label: Status epilepticus with prominent motor symptoms
nodes.def: Status epilepticus with prominent motor signs during the prolonged seizure.

nodes.label: Focal motor status epilepticus
nodes.def: Status epilepticus with focal motor signs originating within networks limited to one hemisphere. Involves musculature in any form. The motor event could consist of an increase (positive) or decrease (negative) in muscle contraction to produce a movement.

nodes.label: Pain in head and neck region
Cerebral palsy
nodes.def: Cerebral palsy describes a group of permanent disorders of the development of movement and posture, causing activity limitation, that are attributed to nonprogressive disturbances that occurred in the developing fetal or infant brain. The motor disorders of cerebral palsy are often accompanied by disturbances of sensation, perception, cognition, communication, and behavior, by epilepsy, and by secondary musculoskeletal problems.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the scalp hair
nodes.def: An abnormality of the hair of head.

nodes.label: Synostosis involving bones of the upper limbs
nodes.def: An abnormal union between bones or parts of bones of the upper limbs.

nodes.label: Sarcoma
nodes.def: A connective tissue neoplasm formed by proliferation of mesodermal cells. Bone and soft tissue sarcomas are the main types of sarcoma. Sarcoma is usually highly malignant.

nodes.label: Skin pit
nodes.def: A small, skin-lined tract that leads from the surface to deep within the tissues.

nodes.label: Aplasia of the phalanges of the 3rd toe
Aplasia of the phalanges of the 4th toe
Aplasia of the phalanges of the 5th toe
Short phalanx of the 3rd toe
nodes.def: Developmental hypoplasia of the phalanx of third toe.

nodes.label: Short phalanx of the 4th toe
nodes.def: Developmental hypoplasia of one or more phalanx of fourth toe.

nodes.label: Short phalanx of the 5th toe
nodes.def: Developmental hypoplasia of one or more phalanx of little toe.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the 3rd toe
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the 4th toe
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the 5th toe
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 3rd toe
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 4th toe
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanx of the 5th toe
Aplasia/hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd toe
nodes.def: Absence (agenesis) or underdevelopment of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd toe.

nodes.label: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of the 4th toe
nodes.def: Absence (agenesis) or underdevelopment of the proximal phalanx of the 4th toe.

nodes.label: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of the 5th toe
nodes.def: Absence (agenesis) or underdevelopment of the proximal phalanx of the 5th toe.

nodes.label: Aplasia of the proximal phalanges of the toes
Conical incisor
nodes.def: An abnormal conical morphology of the incisor tooth.

nodes.label: Abnormal molar morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of morphology of molar tooth.

nodes.label: Abnormality of dental color
nodes.def: A developmental defect of tooth color.

nodes.label: Peripheral demyelination
nodes.def: A loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers of the peripheral nervous system.

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating cytokine concentration
nodes.def: Abnormality of the cytokine levels in the blood, i.e., an abnormality of any of the non-antibody proteins made by inflammatory leukocytes and some non-leukocytic cells that affect the behavior of other cells.

nodes.label: Abnormal nasal dorsum morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the nasal dorsum, also known as the nasal ridge.

nodes.label: Abnormal skin adnexa morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the skin adnexa (skin appendages), which are specialized skin structures located within the dermis and focally within the subcutaneous fatty tissue, comprising three histologically distinct structures: (1) the pilosebaceous unit (hair follicle and sebaceous glands); (2) the eccrine sweat glands; and (3) the apocrine glands.

nodes.label: Malignant neoplasm of the central nervous system
nodes.def: A tumor that originates in the pineal gland, has moderate cellularity and tends to form rosette patterns.

nodes.label: Anaphylactic shock
nodes.def: An acute hypersensitivity reaction due to exposure to a previously encountered antigen.

nodes.label: Aplasia of the musculature
nodes.def: Absence of the musculature.

nodes.label: Abnormal renal medulla morphology
nodes.def: Any structural abnormality of the medulla of the kidney.

nodes.label: Abnormality of fibrinolysis
nodes.def: Clinical phenotype characterized by delayed bleeding accelerated break down of blood clot (fibrinolysis)

nodes.label: Fractured humerus
nodes.def: A partial or complete breakage of the humerus.

nodes.label: Fractured vertebra
nodes.def: A partial or complete breakage of the vertebra.

nodes.label: Fractured middle finger phalanx
nodes.def: A partial or complete breakage of the middle phalanx of a finger.

nodes.label: Fractured tarsal bone
nodes.def: A partial or complete breakage of the tarsal bone.

nodes.label: Abnormal peripheral nerve morphology by anatomical site
nodes.def: Abnormal morphology of a specific peripheral nerve

nodes.label: Abnormal mediastinum morphology
nodes.def: Any structural anomaly of the central compartment of the thoracic cavity.

nodes.label: Osteolysis involving bones of the upper limbs
Positive blood infectious agent test
nodes.def: Any kind of test for an infectious agent in the blood circulation positive.

nodes.label: Abnormal cardiac test
nodes.def: Abnormal test result of cardiovascular physiology.

nodes.label: Elevated circulating porphyrin concentration
nodes.def: Concentration of porphyrins or of a specific porphryin above the upper limit of normal. The most commonly tested circulating porphyrins are coproporphyrin, protoporphyrin, and uroporphyrin. Normally protoporphyrin is present in the highest concentration.

nodes.label: Abnormal enzyme concentration or activity
nodes.def: Concentration or activity of an enzyme is above or below the limits of normal.

nodes.label: Abnormal erythrocyte metabolite concentration
nodes.def: A deviation from the normal range of a metabolite in red blood cells.

nodes.label: Abnormal CSF aspartate family amino acid concentration
nodes.def: Any deviation from the normal concentration of aspartate-family amino acids in the cerebrospinal fluid.

nodes.label: Abnormal communicative facial expressions
nodes.def: Abnormal expressions (movements or position of muscles of the face that convey the emotional state of an individual to observers during social interactions) comprising abnormalities of quantity, range, context-appropriateness, and quality.

nodes.label: Physical urticaria
nodes.def: Urticaria caused by physical agents, such as heat, cold, light, friction.

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase concentration
nodes.def: An anomaly in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase.

nodes.label: Reduced social insight
nodes.def: A lack of awareness of social rules in multiple social settings, which are simple or intuitive to others in the same social setting.

nodes.label: Social disinhibition
nodes.def: A tendency to violate social norms because of a failure to resist temptations or urges in social settings.

nodes.label: Maladaptive fear-related cognitions
nodes.def: Threat-based cognitive biases result in a skewed perception, experience, or processing of internal or external stimuli.

nodes.label: Abnormal demeanor
nodes.def: An anomaly in demeanor, which refers to the outward behavior, manner, or conduct of a person. It encompasses how an individual presents themselves to others in terms of attitude, posture, and general comportment.

nodes.label: Abnormal sleep architecture
nodes.def: Interruptions during the various stages of sleep.

nodes.label: Diminishment of social interactions
nodes.def: A reduction in the tendency of a person to seek or maintain social connections or interactions with others compared to previous norms for an individual.

nodes.label: Abnormal judgment
nodes.def: Beliefs that deviate from what is considered rational or within the range of normal human judgment and belief formation.

nodes.label: Disorder of thought control
nodes.def: A false belief that another person, group of people, or external force controls one's general thoughts, feelings, impulses, or behaviors.

nodes.label: Abnormal ear morphology
nodes.def: Any structural anomaly of the ear.

nodes.label: Non-accomodative esotropia
nodes.def: A form of esotropia in which the angle of deviation is not affected by accommodative effort.

nodes.label: Clinical course
nodes.def: The course a disease typically takes from its onset, progression in time, and eventual resolution or death of the affected individual.

nodes.label: Spinal lipoma
nodes.def: A lipoma that is localized to the spine.

nodes.label: Physeal fracture
nodes.def: Salter-Harris fractures (physeal fractures) refer to fractures through a growth plate (physis) and are, therefore, specifically applied to bone fractures in children.

nodes.label: Abnormal arcuate artery intima/media morphology
nodes.def: Anomalous structure of the inner or middle layer of the arc-shaped arteries located at the border of the renal cortex and renal medulla.

nodes.label: Impaired executive functioning
nodes.def: A disturbance of executive functioning, which is broadly defined as the set of abilities that allow for the planning, executing, monitoring, and self-correcting of goal-directed behavior while inhibiting task-irrelevant behavior. At least some degree of executive skill is needed to complete most cognitive tasks, and deficits in executive abilities are central to many clinical conditions, including fronto-temporal dementia.

nodes.label: Decreased circulating terminal complement component concentration
nodes.def: Concentration below the lower limit of normal of one or more components of the the terminal membrane attack complex (MAC) portion of complement, which represents the lytic, pore-forming part of the system. The MAC comprises seven components: C5b, C6, C7, C8 (a heterotrimer composed of C8alpha, C8beta and C8gamma) and multiple copies of C9.

nodes.label: Abnormal macroscopic urine appearance
nodes.def: Anomalous physical appearance (color, cloudiness, clarity) or odor of urine.

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating calcium-phosphate regulating hormone concentration
nodes.def: Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of a hormone that is involved in the regulation of phosphate and calcium.

nodes.label: Cognitive impairment
nodes.def: Abnormal cognition is characterized by deficits in thinking, reasoning, or remembering.

nodes.label: Arterial stenosis
nodes.def: Narrowing or constriction of the inner surface (lumen) of an artery.

nodes.label: Abnormally ossified vertebrae
nodes.def: An abnormality of the formation and mineralization of one or more vertebrae.

nodes.label: Mucosal telangiectasiae
nodes.def: Telangiectasia of the mucosa, the mucous membranes which are involved in absorption and secretion that line cavities that are exposed to the external environment and internal organs.

nodes.label: Urogenital fistula
nodes.def: The presence of a fistula affecting the genitourinary system.

nodes.label: Calcification of cartilage
nodes.def: The presence of calcium deposition in cartilage.

nodes.label: Neoplasm of the respiratory system
nodes.def: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the respiratory system.

nodes.label: Odontogenic neoplasm
nodes.def: Neoplasm involving odontogenic cells, an odontogenic tumor.

nodes.label: Neuroendocrine neoplasm
nodes.def: A tumor that originates from a neuroendocrine cell.

nodes.label: Abnormal pigmentation of the oral mucosa
nodes.def: An abnormality of the pigmentation of the mucosa of the mouth.

nodes.label: Premature skin wrinkling
nodes.def: The presence of an increased degree of wrinkling (irregular folds and indentations) of the skin as compared with age-related norms.

nodes.label: Abnormal lumbar spine morphology
nodes.def: Any structural abnormality of the lumbar vertebral column.

nodes.label: Abnormal soft palate morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the soft palate.

nodes.label: Esophageal neoplasm
nodes.def: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the esophagus.

nodes.label: Abnormal sacroiliac joint morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of the sacroiliac joint, which connects the base of the spine (sacrum) to the ilium (a hip bone).

nodes.label: Abnormal periungual morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the region around the nails of the fingers or toes.

nodes.label: Mode of inheritance
nodes.def: The pattern in which a particular genetic trait or disorder is passed from one generation to the next.

nodes.label: Hydrocele testis
nodes.def: Accumulation of clear fluid in the between the layers of membrane (tunica vaginalis) surrounding the testis.

nodes.label: Hypospadias
nodes.def: Abnormal position of urethral meatus on the ventral penile shaft (underside) characterized by displacement of the urethral meatus from the tip of the glans penis to the ventral surface of the penis, scrotum, or perineum.

nodes.label: Hypoplastic male external genitalia
nodes.def: Underdevelopment of part or all of the male external reproductive organs (which include the penis, the scrotum and the urethra).

nodes.label: Abnormal clitoris morphology
nodes.def: Any structural abnormality of the clitoris.

nodes.label: Abnormal labia morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of the labia, the externally visible portions of the vulva.

nodes.label: Ureteral duplication
nodes.def: A developmental anomaly characterized by the presence of two, instead of one, ureter connecting a kidney to the bladder.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the urinary system
nodes.def: An abnormality of the urinary system.

nodes.label: Nephritis
nodes.def: The presence of inflammation affecting the kidney.

nodes.label: Renal tubular dysfunction
nodes.def: Abnormal function of the renal tubule. The basic functional unit of the kidney, the nephron, consists of a renal corpuscle attached to a renal tubule, with roughly 0.8 to 1.5 nephrons per adult kidney. The functions of the renal tubule include reabsorption of water, electrolytes, glucose, and amino acids and secretion of substances such as uric acid.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the tongue
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the tongue.

nodes.label: Orofacial cleft
nodes.def: The presence of a cleft (gap, opening, or groove) in the oral cavity, including cleft of the upper lip and/or cleft of the palate. Cleft of the upper lip is visible as a groove or fissure in the lip, most frequently due to a congenital failure of the maxillary and median nasal processes to fuse. Cleft palate is characterized by a grooved depression or fissure in the roof of the mouth, most often resulting from a congenital failure of the palate to fuse properly. Clefts of the lip and palate can occur individually or together. It is preferable to code each defect separately.

nodes.label: Sinusitis
nodes.def: Inflammation of the paranasal sinuses owing to a viral, bacterial, or fungal infection, allergy, or an autoimmune reaction.

nodes.label: Macrocephaly
nodes.def: Occipitofrontal (head) circumference greater than 97th centile compared to appropriate, age matched, sex-matched normal standards. Alternatively, a apparently increased size of the cranium.

nodes.label: Abnormal mastoid morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the mastoid process, which is the conical prominence projecting from the undersurface of the mastoid portion of the temporal bone.

nodes.label: Epicanthus
nodes.def: A fold of skin starting above the medial aspect of the upper eyelid and arching downward to cover, pass in front of and lateral to the medial canthus.

nodes.label: Abnormal midface morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of the midface, which is a region and not an anatomical term. It extends, superiorly, from the inferior orbital margin to, inferiorly, the level of nasal base. It is formed by the maxilla (upper jaw) and zygoma and cheeks and malar region. Traditionally, the nose and premaxilla are not included in the midface.

nodes.label: Facial hemangioma
nodes.def: Hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, occurring in the face.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the outer ear
nodes.def: An abnormality of the external ear.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the inner ear
nodes.def: An abnormality of the inner ear.

nodes.label: Hearing abnormality
nodes.def: An abnormality of the sensory perception of sound.

nodes.label: Abnormal cochlea morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the cochlea.

nodes.label: Abnormality of refraction
nodes.def: An abnormality in the process of focusing of light by the eye in order to produce a sharp image on the retina.

nodes.label: External ophthalmoplegia
nodes.def: Paralysis of the external ocular muscles.

nodes.label: Absent eyelashes
nodes.def: Lack of eyelashes.

nodes.label: Macular degeneration
nodes.def: A nonspecific term denoting degeneration of the retinal pigment epithelium and/or retinal photoreceptor cells of the macula lutea.

nodes.label: Abnormality of ocular smooth pursuit
nodes.def: An abnormality of eye movement characterized by impaired smooth-pursuit eye movements.

nodes.label: Entropion
nodes.def: An abnormal inversion (turning inward) of the eyelid (usually the lower) towards the globe. Entropion is usually acquired as a result of involutional or cicatricial processes but may occasionally be congenital.

nodes.label: Red-green dyschromatopsia
nodes.def: Difficulty with discriminating red and green hues.

nodes.label: Abnormality of visual evoked potentials
nodes.def: An anomaly of visually evoked potentials (VEP), which are electrical potentials, initiated by brief visual stimuli, which are recorded from the scalp overlying the visual cortex.

nodes.label: Ectropion
nodes.def: An outward turning (eversion) or rotation of the eyelid margin.

nodes.label: Microdontia
nodes.def: Decreased size of the teeth, which can be defined as a mesiodistal tooth diameter (width) more than 2 SD below mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased maximum width of tooth.

nodes.label: Dentinogenesis imperfecta
nodes.def: Developmental dysplasia of dentin.

nodes.label: Dementia
nodes.def: A loss of global cognitive ability of sufficient amount to interfere with normal social or occupational function. Dementia represents a loss of previously present cognitive abilities, generally in adults, and can affect memory, thinking, language, judgment, and behavior.

nodes.label: Abnormal nonverbal communicative behavior
nodes.def: Abnormalities in eye contact, communicative facial expressions, gesture use, or the use of others' bodies to communicate convey shared meanings within a culture that replace or supplement verbal communication.

nodes.label: Sensory neuropathy
nodes.def: Peripheral neuropathy affecting the sensory nerves.

nodes.label: Hematuria
nodes.def: The presence of blood in the urine. Hematuria may be gross hematuria (visible to the naked eye) or microscopic hematuria (detected by dipstick or microscopic examination of the urine).

nodes.label: Hypothyroidism
nodes.def: Deficiency of thyroid hormone.

nodes.label: Delayed puberty
nodes.def: Passing the age when puberty normally occurs with no physical or hormonal signs of the onset of puberty.

nodes.label: Abnormality of renin-angiotensin system
nodes.def: An abnormality of the renin-angiotensin system.

nodes.label: Goiter
nodes.def: An enlargement of the thyroid gland.

nodes.label: Thyroid adenoma
nodes.def: The presence of a adenoma of the thyroid gland.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the skeletal system
nodes.def: An abnormality of the skeletal system.

nodes.label: Hypoplastic ilia
nodes.def: Underdevelopment of the ilium.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the skin
nodes.def: An abnormality of the skin.

nodes.label: Cyanosis
nodes.def: Bluish discoloration of the skin and mucosa due to poor circulation or inadequate oxygenation of arterial or capillary blood.

nodes.label: Facial capillary hemangioma
nodes.def: Hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells with small endothelial spaces, occurring in the face.

nodes.label: Urticaria
nodes.def: Raised, well-circumscribed areas of erythema and edema involving the dermis and epidermis. Urticaria is intensely pruritic, and blanches completely with pressure.

nodes.label: Nevus flammeus
nodes.def: A congenital vascular malformation consisting of superficial and deep dilated capillaries in the skin which produce a reddish to purplish discolouration of the skin.

nodes.label: Thickened skin
nodes.def: Laminar thickening of skin.

nodes.label: Keratitis
nodes.def: Inflammation of the cornea.

nodes.label: Abnormal electroretinogram
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the electrical responses of various cell types in the retina as measured by electroretinography.

nodes.label: Truncus arteriosus
nodes.def: A single arterial trunk arises from the cardiac mass. The pulmonary arteries, aorta and coronary arteries arise from this single trunk with no evidence of another outflow tract.

nodes.label: Coarctation of aorta
nodes.def: Coarctation of the aorta is a narrowing or constriction of a segment of the aorta.

nodes.label: Pericardial effusion
nodes.def: Accumulation of fluid within the pericardium.

nodes.label: Abnormal nasopharynx morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of the nasopharynx.

nodes.label: Single ventricle
nodes.def: The presence of only one working lower chamber in the heart, usually with a virtual absence of the ventricular septum and usually present in conjunction with double inlet left or right ventricle.

nodes.label: Onycholysis
nodes.def: Detachment of the nail from the nail bed.

nodes.label: Talipes
nodes.def: A deformity of foot and ankle that has different subtypes that are talipes equinovarus, talipes equinovalgus, talipes calcaneovarus and talipes calcaneovalgus.

nodes.label: Megaloblastic anemia
nodes.def: Anemia characterized by the presence of erythroblasts that are larger than normal (megaloblasts).

nodes.label: Subcutaneous hemorrhage
nodes.def: This term refers to an abnormally increased susceptibility to bruising (purpura, petechiae, or ecchymoses).

nodes.label: Alkalosis
nodes.def: Depletion of acid or accumulation base in the body fluids.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of metatarsal bones
nodes.def: Absence or underdevelopment of the metatarsal bones.

nodes.label: Macrocytic anemia
nodes.def: A type of anemia characterized by increased size of erythrocytes with increased mean corpuscular volume (MCV) and increased mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH).

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of toe
nodes.def: Absence or hypoplasia of toes.

nodes.label: Ketoacidosis
nodes.def: Acidosis resulting from accumulation of ketone bodies.

nodes.label: Cerebral atrophy
nodes.def: Atrophy (wasting, decrease in size of cells or tissue) affecting the cerebrum.

nodes.label: Rigidity
nodes.def: Continuous involuntary sustained muscle contraction. When an affected muscle is passively stretched, the degree of resistance remains constant regardless of the rate at which the muscle is stretched. This feature helps to distinguish rigidity from muscle spasticity.

nodes.label: Bilateral tonic-clonic seizure
nodes.def: A bilateral tonic-clonic seizure is a seizure defined by a tonic (bilateral increased tone, lasting seconds to minutes) and then a clonic (bilateral sustained rhythmic jerking) phase.

nodes.label: Pneumonia
nodes.def: Inflammation of any part of the lung parenchyma.

nodes.label: Asthma
nodes.def: Asthma is characterized by increased responsiveness of the tracheobronchial tree to multiple stimuli, leading to narrowing of the air passages with resultant dyspnea, cough, and wheezing.

nodes.label: Status epilepticus
nodes.def: Status epilepticus is a type of prolonged seizure resulting either from the failure of the mechanisms responsible for seizure termination or from the initiation of mechanisms which lead to abnormally prolonged seizures (after time point t1). It is a condition that can have long-term consequences (after time point t2), including neuronal death, neuronal injury, and alteration of neuronal networks, depending on the type and duration of seizures.

nodes.label: Clonus
nodes.def: A series of rhythmic and involuntary muscle contractions (at a frequency of about 5 to 7 Hz) that occur in response to an abruptly applied and sustained stretch.

nodes.label: Aganglionic megacolon
nodes.def: An abnormality resulting from a lack of intestinal ganglion cells (i.e., an aganglionic section of bowel) that results in bowel obstruction with enlargement of the colon.

nodes.label: Developmental glaucoma
nodes.def: Glaucoma which forms during the early years of a child's life is called developmental or congenital glaucoma.

nodes.label: Retinal atrophy
nodes.def: Well-demarcated area(s) of partial or complete depigmentation in the fundus, reflecting atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium with associated retinal photoreceptor loss.

nodes.label: Abnormalities of placenta or umbilical cord
nodes.def: An abnormality of the placenta (the organ that connects the developing fetus to the uterine wall) or of the umbilical cord (the cord that connects the fetus to the placenta).

nodes.label: Global developmental delay
nodes.def: A delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child, including motor skills, speech and language, cognitive skills, and social and emotional skills. This term should only be used to describe children younger than five years of age.

nodes.label: Hypertonia
nodes.def: A condition in which there is increased muscle tone so that arms or legs, for example, are stiff and difficult to move.

nodes.label: Syncope
nodes.def: Syncope is a syndrome in which loss of consciousness is of relatively sudden onset, temporary (usually less than 1 to 2 minutes), self-terminating, and of usually rapid recovery. Syncope leads to a generalized weakness of muscles with loss of postural tone, inability to stand upright, and loss of consciousness. Once the patient is in a horizontal position, blood flow to the brain is no longer hindered by gravitation and consciousness is regained. Unconsciousness usually lasts for seconds to minutes. Headache and drowsiness (which usually follow seizures) do not follow a syncopal attack. Syncope results from a sudden impairment of brain metabolism usually due to a reduction in cerebral blood flow.

nodes.label: Stroke
nodes.def: Sudden impairment of blood flow to a part of the brain due to occlusion or rupture of an artery to the brain.

nodes.label: Specific learning disability
nodes.def: Impairment of certain skills such as reading or writing, coordination, self-control, or attention that interfere with the ability to learn. The impairment is not related to a global deficiency of intelligence.

nodes.label: Tremor
nodes.def: An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement about a joint axis.

nodes.label: Joint hypermobility
nodes.def: The capability that a joint (or a group of joints) has to move, passively and/or actively, beyond normal limits along physiological axes.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the liver
nodes.def: An abnormality of the liver.

nodes.label: Hepatic steatosis
nodes.def: Steatosis is a term used to denote lipid accumulation within hepatocytes.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the musculature of the upper limbs
nodes.def: Absence or underdevelopment of the musculature of the upper limbs.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the musculature of the pelvis
Abnormality of the integument
nodes.def: An abnormality of the integument, which consists of the skin and the superficial fascia.

nodes.label: Selective tooth agenesis
nodes.def: Agenesis specifically affecting one of the classes incisor, premolar, or molar.

nodes.label: Vocal cord paralysis
nodes.def: A loss of the ability to move the vocal folds.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the cardiovascular system
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the cardiovascular system.

nodes.label: Bowed forearm bones
nodes.def: A bending or abnormal curvature affecting either the radius, the ulna, or both.

nodes.label: Absent radius
nodes.def: Missing radius bone associated with congenital failure of development.

nodes.label: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 4th finger
nodes.def: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 4th (ring) finger.

nodes.label: Symphalangism of the 4th finger
nodes.def: Fusion of two or more bones of the 4th finger.

nodes.label: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 5th finger
nodes.def: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the phalanges of the 5th finger.

nodes.label: Symphalangism of the 5th finger
nodes.def: Fusion of two or more bones of the 5th finger.

nodes.label: Synostosis involving bones of the hand
nodes.def: An abnormal union between bones or parts of bones of the hand.

nodes.label: Abnormal anatomic location of the heart
nodes.def: Developmental defect characterized by an anomalous anatomic location of the heart.

nodes.label: Vaginal fistula
nodes.def: The presence of a fistula of the vagina.

nodes.label: Bladder fistula
nodes.def: The presence of a fistula connecting the urinary bladder to another organ or the skin. The fistula can involve the bowel, the vagina, or rarely, the skin.

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating purine concentration
nodes.def: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a purine in the blood circulation.

nodes.label: Increased circulating purine concentration
nodes.def: Abnormally elevated concentration of a purine compound. Purine compounds are aromatic heterocyclic compounds containing a purine moiety, which is formed a pyrimidine-ring ring fused to an imidazole ring.

nodes.label: Hamartomatous polyposis
nodes.def: Polyp-like protrusions which are histologically hamartomas. These can occur throughout the gastrointestinal tract. Hamartomatous polyps are composed of the normal cellular elements of the gastrointestinal tract, but have a markedly distorted architecture.

nodes.label: Beaking of vertebral bodies
nodes.def: Anterior tongue-like protrusions of the vertebral bodies.

nodes.label: Supraventricular tachycardia
nodes.def: Supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) is an abnormally increased heart rate (over 100 beats per minute at rest) with origin above the level of the ventricles.

nodes.label: Recurrent infection of the gastrointestinal tract
nodes.def: Recurrent infection of the gastrointestinal tract.

nodes.label: Elevated pulmonary artery pressure
nodes.def: An abnormally elevated blood pressure in the circulation of the pulmonary artery.

nodes.label: Elevated circulating hepatic transaminase concentration
nodes.def: Elevations of the levels of SGOT and SGPT in the serum. SGOT (serum glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase) and SGPT (serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase) are transaminases primarily found in the liver and heart and are released into the bloodstream as the result of liver or heart damage. SGOT and SGPT are used clinically mainly as markers of liver damage.

nodes.label: Hemivertebrae
nodes.def: Absence of one half of the vertebral body.

nodes.label: Femoral bowing
nodes.def: Bowing (abnormal curvature) of the femur.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the musculature
nodes.def: Abnormality originating in one or more muscles, i.e., of the set of muscles of body.

nodes.label: Metaphyseal widening
nodes.def: Abnormal widening of the metaphyseal regions of long bones.

nodes.label: Hypoplasia of the ulna
nodes.def: Underdevelopment of the ulna.

nodes.label: Slender long bone
nodes.def: Reduced diameter of a long bone.

nodes.label: Elevated circulating alkaline phosphatase concentration
nodes.def: Abnormally increased serum levels of alkaline phosphatase activity.

nodes.label: Abnormal pubic bone morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of the the pubic bone, i.e., of the ventral and anterior of the three principal components (pubis, ilium, ischium) of the hip bone.

nodes.label: Abnormal ischium morphology
nodes.def: An anomaly of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.

nodes.label: Increased circulating IgE concentration
nodes.def: An abnormally increased overall level of immunoglobulin E in blood.

nodes.label: Elevated circulating creatine kinase concentration
nodes.def: An elevation of the level of the enzyme creatine kinase (also known as creatine phosphokinase (CK; EC 2.7.3.2) in the blood. CK levels can be elevated in a number of clinical disorders such as myocardial infarction, rhabdomyolysis, and muscular dystrophy.

nodes.label: Increased circulating IgA concentration
nodes.def: An abnormally increased level of immunoglobulin A in blood.

nodes.label: Abnormal odontoid process morphology
nodes.def: Abnormal structure of the odontoid process, which is a part of the C2 or axis vertebra and forms pivot of the structures forming the craniovertebral junction. The odontoid process is also known as the dens of the axis.

nodes.label: Disturbance of facial expression
nodes.def: An abnormality of the gestures or movements executed with the facial muscles with which emotions such as fear, joy, sadness, surprise, and disgust can be expressed.

nodes.label: Abnormality of humoral immunity
nodes.def: An abnormality of the humoral immune system, which comprises antibodies produced by B cells as well as the complement system.

nodes.label: Recurrent bacterial skin infections
nodes.def: Increased susceptibility to bacterial infections of the skin, as manifested by recurrent episodes of infectious dermatitis.

nodes.label: Decreased circulating IgE concentration
nodes.def: An abnormally decreased level of immunoglobulin E (IgE) in blood.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the tibia
nodes.def: Absence or underdevelopment of the tibia.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the Achilles tendon
nodes.def: An abnormality of the Achilles tendon.

nodes.label: Supraventricular arrhythmia
nodes.def: A type of arrhythmia that originates above the ventricles, whereby the electrical impulse propagates down the normal His Purkinje system similar to normal sinus rhythm.

nodes.label: Cardiac valve calcification
nodes.def: Abnormal calcification of a cardiac valve.

nodes.label: Total anomalous pulmonary venous return
nodes.def: Total anomalous pulmonary venous return refers to a congenital malformation in which all four pulmonary veins do not connect normally to the left atrium, but instead drain abnormally to the right atrium.

nodes.label: Intestinal obstruction
nodes.def: Blockage or impairment of the normal flow of the contents of the intestine towards the anal canal.

nodes.label: Gastritis
nodes.def: The presence of inflammation of the gastric mucous membrane.

nodes.label: Abnormal jejunum morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the jejunum, i.e., of the middle section of the small intestine.

nodes.label: Broad phalanx
nodes.def: Increased side-to-side width of one or more phalanges of the fingers or toes.

nodes.label: Mesoaxial hand polydactyly
nodes.def: The presence of a supernumerary finger (not a thumb) involving the third or fourth metacarpal with associated osseous syndactyly.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the 5th finger
nodes.def: A small/hypoplastic or absent/aplastic 5th finger.

nodes.label: Radial ray deficiency
nodes.def: Radial dysplasia, also known as radial longitudinal deficiency, includes radial clubhand and is a disfiguring, and potentially disabling, congenital limb anomaly. The entire upper limb may be involved, although the defect is most evident in the forearm and hand. Affected children suffer a variable degree of hypoplasia or absence of the preaxial skeleton and soft tissues, in particular the thumb, radius, and dorsoradial soft tissues. The hand is usually radially deviated and subluxated off the distal aspect of the ulna, the ulna may be shortened and have a bow-shaped deformity, and there is no true wrist (radiocarpal) joint in Bayne2 type-III and IV radial dysplasia.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the pancreatic islet cells
nodes.def: An abnormality of the islet of Langerhans, i.e., of the regions of the pancreas that contain its endocrine cells. These are the alpha cells, which produce glucagon, the beta cells, which produce insulin and amylin, the delta cells, which produce somatostatin, the PP cells, which produce pancreatic polypeptide, and the epsilon cells, which produce ghrelin.

nodes.label: Abnormal dental pulp morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the dental pulp.

nodes.label: Abnormal number of teeth
nodes.def: The presence of an altered number of of teeth.

nodes.label: Abnormal dental root morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the dental root.

nodes.label: Bowing of the long bones
nodes.def: A bending or abnormal curvature of a long bone.

nodes.label: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the humerus
nodes.def: Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of the humerus.

nodes.label: Sleep-wake cycle disturbance
nodes.def: Any abnormality of an individual's circadian rhythm that affects the timing of sleeping and being awake is referred to as a sleep-wake disorder.

nodes.label: Pseudobulbar paralysis
nodes.def: Bilateral impairment of the function of the cranial nerves 9-12, which control musculature involved in eating, swallowing, and speech. Pseudobulbar paralysis is characterized clinically by dysarthria, dysphonia, and dysphagia with bifacial paralysis, and may be accompanied by Pseudobulbar behavioral symptoms such as enforced crying and laughing.

nodes.label: Demyelinating peripheral neuropathy
nodes.def: Demyelinating neuropathy is characterized by slow nerve conduction velocities with reduced amplitudes of sensory/motor nerve conduction and prolonged distal latencies.

nodes.label: Spinal muscular atrophy
nodes.def: Muscular weakness and atrophy related to loss of the motor neurons of the spinal cord and brainstem.

nodes.label: CNS demyelination
nodes.def: A loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system.

nodes.label: Memory impairment
nodes.def: An impairment of memory as manifested by a reduced ability to remember things such as dates and names, and increased forgetfulness.

nodes.label: Aphasia
nodes.def: An acquired language impairment of some or all of the abilities to produce or comprehend speech and to read or write.

nodes.label: Abnormal globus pallidus morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the globus pallidus.

nodes.label: Upper motor neuron dysfunction
nodes.def: A functional anomaly of the upper motor neuron. The upper motor neurons are neurons of the primary motor cortex which project to the brainstem and spinal chord via the corticonuclear, corticobulbar and corticospinal (pyramidal) tracts. They are involved in control of voluntary movements. Dysfunction leads to weakness, impairment of fine motor movements, spasticity, hyperreflexia and abnormal pyramidal signs.

nodes.label: Abnormal rapid eye movement sleep
nodes.def: Abnormality of REM Sleep are phases of REM sleep are characterized by desynchronized EEG patterns, increases in heart rate and blood pressure, sympathetic activation, and a profound loss of muscle tone except for the eye and middle-ear muscles. There are also phases of rapid eye movements.

nodes.label: Gastrointestinal dysmotility
nodes.def: Abnormal intestinal contractions, such as spasms and intestinal paralysis, related to the loss of the ability of the gut to coordinate muscular activity because of endogenous or exogenous causes.

nodes.label: Hypotension
nodes.def: Low Blood Pressure, vascular hypotension.

nodes.label: Lymphoma
nodes.def: A cancer originating in lymphocytes and presenting as a solid tumor of lymhpoid cells.

nodes.label: Decreased circulating IgA concentration
nodes.def: Decreased levels of immunoglobulin A (IgA).

nodes.label: Kyphoscoliosis
nodes.def: An abnormal curvature of the spine in both a coronal (lateral) and sagittal (back-to-front) plane.

nodes.label: Mucopolysacchariduria
nodes.def: Excessive amounts of mucopolysaccharide in the urine.

nodes.label: Pancreatic islet cell adenoma
nodes.def: The presence of an adenoma of the pancreas with origin in a pancreatic B cell.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the hallux
nodes.def: Absence or underdevelopment of the big toe.

nodes.label: Foot joint contracture
nodes.def: Contractures of one or more joints of the feet meaning chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the nails
nodes.def: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the nail.

nodes.label: Abnormal synaptic transmission at the neuromuscular junction
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the neuromuscular junction, which is the synapse between the motor end plate of a motor neuron and the skeletal muscle fibers.

nodes.label: Back pain
nodes.def: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the back.

nodes.label: Vertebral segmentation defect
nodes.def: An abnormality related to a defect of vertebral separation during development.

nodes.label: Fatigable weakness
nodes.def: A type of weakness that occurs after a muscle group is used and lessens if the muscle group has some rest. That is, there is diminution of strength with repetitive muscle actions.

nodes.label: Somatic sensory dysfunction
nodes.def: An abnormality of the primary sensation that is mediated by peripheral nerves (pain, temperature, touch, vibration, joint position). The word hypoesthesia (or hypesthesia) refers to a reduction in cutaneous sensation to a specific type of testing.

nodes.label: Peripheral axonal neuropathy
nodes.def: An abnormality characterized by disruption of the normal functioning of peripheral axons.

nodes.label: Increased circulating IgM level
nodes.def: An abnormally increased level of immunoglobulin M in blood.

nodes.label: Distal amyotrophy
nodes.def: Muscular atrophy affecting muscles in the distal portions of the extremities.

nodes.label: Limb-girdle muscle atrophy
nodes.def: Muscular atrophy affecting the muscles of the limb girdle.

nodes.label: Muscle abnormality related to mitochondrial dysfunction
Flared upper limb metaphysis
nodes.def: The presence of a splayed (i.e.,flared) metaphyseal segment of one or more long bones of the arm.

nodes.label: Upper limb metaphyseal widening
nodes.def: Increased width (breadth) of metaphyses of the arms.

nodes.label: Irregular ossification of the humeral epiphyses
Distal lower limb muscle weakness
nodes.def: Reduced strength of the distal musculature of the legs.

nodes.label: Abnormal ossification of the pubic bone
nodes.def: Abnormal ossification (bone tissue formation) affecting the pubic bone, also known as the pubis.

nodes.label: Scapulohumeral synostosis
nodes.def: Bony fusion between the humerus and scapula, leading to an impairment in mobility of the affected shoulder joint.

nodes.label: Triangular epiphyses of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the 3rd finger of the hand.

nodes.label: Symphalangism of middle phalanx of 3rd finger
nodes.def: Fusion of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger with another bone.

nodes.label: Broad phalanges of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: Increased width of the phalanges of the 3rd finger.

nodes.label: Bullet-shaped phalanges of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: A third finger with short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

nodes.label: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: Dissolution or degeneration of bone tissue of the phalanges of the 3rd finger.

nodes.label: Patchy sclerosis of 3rd finger phalanx
nodes.def: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the third finger.

nodes.label: Symphalangism of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: Fusion of two or more bones of the 3rd finger.

nodes.label: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: Triangular shaped phalanges of the 3rd finger. A triangular or so called delta shaped phalanx is a typical result after a bracket epiphysis of the affected phalanx.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 3rd finger
Symphalangism affecting the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger with another bone.

nodes.label: Aplasia of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: Absent 3rd finger.

nodes.label: Short 3rd finger
nodes.def: Hypoplastic/small 3rd (middle) finger.

nodes.label: Deviation of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Displacement of the 2nd finger from its normal position.

nodes.label: Absent epiphyses of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Absence of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger.

nodes.label: Bracket epiphyses of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: An abnormality of the second finger in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

nodes.label: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: A cone-shaped appearance of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger of the hand, producing a 'ball-in-a-socket' appearance. The related entity 'angel-shaped' epiphysis refers to a pronounced cone-shaped epiphysis in combination with a pseudoepiphysis at the distal end of a phalanx.

nodes.label: Enlarged epiphyses of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Abnormally large size of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

nodes.label: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger.

nodes.label: Irregular epiphyses of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Irregular radiographic opacity of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger.

nodes.label: Pseudoepiphysis of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: A secondary ossification center in the second finger that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

nodes.label: Small epiphyses of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Abnormally small size of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger with respect to age-dependent norms.

nodes.label: Stippling of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of the 2nd finger.

nodes.label: Triangular epiphyses of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: A triangular appearance of the epiphyses of the 2nd finger of the hand.

nodes.label: Aplasia of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Absent 2nd (index) finger.

nodes.label: Short 2nd finger
nodes.def: Hypoplasia of the second finger, also known as the index finger.

nodes.label: Flexion contracture of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Chronic loss of joint motion in the 2nd finger due to structural changes in non-bony tissue. The term camptodactyly of the 2nd finger is used if the distal and/or proximal interphalangeal joints are affected.

nodes.label: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the 2nd finger
Patchy sclerosis of 2nd finger phalanx
nodes.def: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the phalanges of the 2nd finger.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 2nd finger
Abnormality of the hairline
nodes.def: The hairline refers to the outline of hair of the head. An abnormality of the hairline can refer to an unusually low or high border between areas of the scalp with and without hair or to abnormal projections of scalp hair.

nodes.label: Symphalangism of middle phalanx of 2nd finger
nodes.def: Fusion of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger with another bone.

nodes.label: Symphalangism affecting the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Fusion of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger with another bone.

nodes.label: Vestibular schwannoma
nodes.def: A vestibular schwannoma (also known as acoustic neuroma, acoustic neurinoma, or acoustic neurilemoma) is a benign, usually slow-growing tumor that develops from the VIIIth cranial nerve supplying the inner ear.

nodes.label: Astrocytoma
nodes.def: Astrocytoma is a neoplasm of the central nervous system derived from astrocytes. Astrocytes are a type of glial cell, and thus astrocytoma is a subtype of glioma.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the thumb
nodes.def: Hypoplastic/small or absent thumb.

nodes.label: Duplication of the distal phalanx of the thumb
nodes.def: Complete or partial duplication of the distal phalanx of the thumb. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx), a partially fused appearance of the two bones, or two separate bones appearing side to side.

nodes.label: Duplication of the proximal phalanx of the thumb
nodes.def: Complete or partial duplication of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. Depending on the severity, the appearance on x-ray can vary from a notched phalanx (the duplicated bone is almost completely fused with the phalanx), a partially fused appearance of the two bones, or two separate bones appearing side to side. In contrast to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, the proximal phalanx of the thumb is embryologically equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits, whereas the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the other digits.

nodes.label: Curved thumb phalanx
nodes.def: A deviation from the normal straight shape of a thumb phalanx.

nodes.label: Partial absence of thumb
nodes.def: The absence of a phalangeal segment of a thumb.

nodes.label: Short phalanx of the thumb
nodes.def: Hypoplastic (short) thumb phalanx.

nodes.label: Ivory epiphysis of the thumb
nodes.def: Sclerosis of one or more of the epiphyses of the thumb, leading to an increased degree of radiopacity (white or ivory appearance) in X-rays.

nodes.label: Contracture of the distal interphalangeal joint of the fingers
nodes.def: Chronic loss of joint motion in one or more distal interphalangeal joints of the fingers.

nodes.label: Abnormal subungual morphology
nodes.def: A lesion located beneath a fingernail or toenail.

nodes.label: Cerebral hamartoma
nodes.def: The presence of a hamartoma of the cerebrum.

nodes.label: Aplasia of the phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: Absence of one or more of the phalanges of the hand.

nodes.label: Phocomelia
nodes.def: Missing or malformed long bones of the extremities with the distal parts (such as hands and/or feet) connected to the variably shortened or even absent extremity, leading to a flipper-like appearance, as opposed to other forms of limb malformations were either the hole limb is missing (such as amelia), or the distal part of a limb is absent (peromelia).

nodes.label: Abnormal vestibulo-ocular reflex
nodes.def: An abnormality of the vestibulo-ocular reflex (VOR). The VOR attempts to keep the image stable on the retina. Ideally passive or active head movements in one direction are compensated for by eye movements of equal magnitude.

nodes.label: Uveal melanoma
nodes.def: A malignant melanoma originating within the eye. The tumor originates from the melanocytes in the uvea (which comprises the iris, ciliary body, and choroid).

nodes.label: Remnants of the hyaloid vascular system
nodes.def: Persistence of the hyaloid artery, which is the embryonic artery that runs from the optic disc to the posterior lens capsule may persist; the site of attachment may form an opacity. The hyaloid artery is a branch of the ophthalmic artery, and usually regresses completely before birth. This features results from a failure of regression of the hyaloid vessel, which supplies the primary vitreous during embryogenesis and normally regresses in the third trimester of pregnancy, leading to a particular form of posterior cataract.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the iris
nodes.def: Absence or underdevelopment of the iris.

nodes.label: Abnormal morphology of the conjunctival vasculature
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the blood vessels of the conjunctiva.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia affecting the anterior segment of the eye
nodes.def: Absence or underdevelopment of the anterior segment of the eye.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the fifth metatarsal bone
nodes.def: An anomaly of the fifth metatarsal bone.

nodes.label: Abnormal temporal bone morphology
nodes.def: Abnormality of the temporal bone of the skull, which is situated at the sides and base of the skull roughly underlying the region of the face known as the temple.

nodes.label: Abnormal tragus morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the tragus.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the nose
nodes.def: Underdevelopment or absence of the nose or parts thereof.

nodes.label: Duplication of the proximal phalanx of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the second proximal phalanx of hand.

nodes.label: Duplication of the distal phalanx of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of index finger.

nodes.label: Duplication of the middle phalanx of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the middle phalanx of index finger.

nodes.label: Partial duplication of the phalanges of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 2nd finger. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.

nodes.label: Complete duplication of the phalanges of the 2nd finger
nodes.def: A complete duplication affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 2nd finger. As opposed to a partial duplication were there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones, a complete duplication leads to two separate bones appearing side to side (radio-ulnar axis) as seen on x-rays. A duplication leading to an accessory bone appearing in the proximo-distal axis on x-rays, is a different entity called a Pseudoepiphyses (see according terms) sometimes also referred to as Hyperphalangism.

nodes.label: Complete duplication of the phalanges of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: A complete duplication affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 3rd finger. As opposed to a partial duplication were there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones, a complete duplication leads to two separate bones appearing side to side (radio-ulnar axis) as seen on x-rays. A duplication leading to an accessory bone appearing in the proximo-distal axis on x-rays, this is actually a different entity called a Pseudoepiphyses (see according terms) sometimes also referred to as Hyperphalangism.

nodes.label: Partial duplication of the phalanges of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 3rd finger. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.

nodes.label: Duplication of the distal phalanx of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of middle finger.

nodes.label: Duplication of the middle phalanx of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the middle phalanx of middle finger.

nodes.label: Duplication of the proximal phalanx of the 3rd finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the third proximal phalanx of hand.

nodes.label: Complete duplication of the phalanges of the 4th finger
nodes.def: A complete duplication affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 4th finger. As opposed to a partial duplication were there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones, a complete duplication leads to two separate bones appearing side to side (radio-ulnar axis) as seen on x-rays. A duplication leading to an accessory bone appearing in the proximo-distal axis on x-rays, this is actually a different entity called a Pseudoepiphyses (see according terms) sometimes also referred to as Hyperphalangism.

nodes.label: Partial duplication of the phalanges of the 4th finger
nodes.def: A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 4th finger. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.

nodes.label: Duplication of the distal phalanx of the 4th finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of ring finger.

nodes.label: Duplication of the middle phalanx of the 4th finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the middle phalanx of ring finger.

nodes.label: Duplication of the proximal phalanx of the 4th finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the fourth proximal phalanx of hand.

nodes.label: Complete duplication of the phalanges of the 5th finger
nodes.def: A complete duplication affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 5th finger. As opposed to a partial duplication were there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones, a complete duplication leads to two separate bones appearing side to side (radio-ulnar axis) as seen on x-rays. A duplication leading to an accessory bone appearing in the proximo-distal axis on x-rays, this is actually a different entity called a Pseudoepiphyses (see according terms) sometimes also referred to as Hyperphalangism.

nodes.label: Partial duplication of the phalanges of the 5th finger
nodes.def: A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the phalanges of the 5th finger. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.

nodes.label: Duplication of the distal phalanx of the 5th finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the distal phalanx of little finger.

nodes.label: Duplication of the middle phalanx of the 5th finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the fifth middle phalanx of hand.

nodes.label: Duplication of the proximal phalanx of the 5th finger
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the fifth proximal phalanx of hand.

nodes.label: Abnormal 5th metacarpal morphology
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the fifth metacarpal bone.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the 1st metacarpal
nodes.def: Aplasia or Hypoplasia affecting the 1st metacarpal. In contrast to the metacarpals 2-5, the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5 (whereas the proximal phalanx of the thumb is equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits).

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the 2nd metacarpal
nodes.def: Aplasia or Hypoplasia affecting the 2nd metacarpal.

nodes.label: Osteolytic defects of the phalanges of the hallux
Triangular shaped phalanges of the hallux
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the distal phalanx of the hallux
Duplication of the distal phalanx of the hallux
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the proximal phalanx of the hallux
Symphalangism affecting the proximal phalanx of the hallux
Duplication of the proximal phalanx of the hallux
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of the proximal phalanx of big toe.

nodes.label: Short phalanx of hallux
nodes.def: Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of a phalanx of big toe.

nodes.label: Mesoaxial foot polydactyly
nodes.def: The presence of a supernumerary toe (not a hallux) involving the third or fourth metatarsal with associated osseous syndactyly.

nodes.label: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the hallux
Flexion contracture of the hallux
nodes.def: One or more bent (flexed) joints of the first (big) toe that cannot be straightened actively or passively.

nodes.label: Cleft maxillary alveolar ridge
nodes.def: A gap (cleft) affecting one of the alveolar ridges, which are the protuberances in the mouth that contain the sockets (alveoli) of the teeth. An alveolar cleft can affect all structures of the alveolar ridge, including the gingiva, other mucosa, periosteum, alveolar bone, and teeth. Alveolar cleft occurs in response to divergence from normal development during frontonasal prominence growth, contact, and fusion. The most common alveolar portion of the cleft is located between the lateral incisor and the canine.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the sacrum
nodes.def: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the sacral bone.

nodes.label: Abnormal stapes morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the stapes, a stirrup-shaped ossicle in the middle ear.

nodes.label: Abnormal spermatogenesis
nodes.def: Incomplete maturation or aberrant formation of the male gametes.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the temporomandibular joint
nodes.def: An anomaly of the temporomandibular joint.

nodes.label: Palmar hyperkeratosis
nodes.def: Abnormal thickening of the skin localized to the palm of the hand.

nodes.label: Sacrococcygeal pilonidal abnormality
nodes.def: The presence of a cyst, fistula, or abscess in the sacrococcygeal region (gluteal crease) characteristically accompanied by hair and skin folds.

nodes.label: Gonadal neoplasm
nodes.def: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of a gonad.

nodes.label: Urinary tract neoplasm
nodes.def: The presence of a neoplasm of the urinary system.

nodes.label: Genital neoplasm
nodes.def: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the genital system.

nodes.label: Impaired proprioception
nodes.def: A loss or impairment of the sensation of the relative position of parts of the body and joint position.

nodes.label: EEG with photoparoxysmal response
nodes.def: EEG abnormalities (epileptiform discharges) evoked by flashing lights or black and white striped patterns.

nodes.label: Receptive language delay
nodes.def: A delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.
